 Archchancellor of [[Unseen University]], leads a small group of faculty to attend the wedding.  Along the way, they are joined by the Dwarfish lothario [[Casanunda]].\n\nGranny and Nanny discover that a group of local girls, led by [[Witches (Discworld)#Diamanda Tockley|Diamanda Tockley]] and including  [[Agnes Nitt]], have formed a new coven whose activities include dancing naked at the Dancers.  The two elderly witches try to convince them to stop, with Granny ultimately besting Diamanda in a public witchcraft contest and discrediting the new coven.  But a defiant Diamanda later runs through the Dancers into the land of the Elves, where she is knocked unconscious by a poisoned Elven arrow before being rescued by Granny.  Nanny subdues an Elf that pursues them back into Lancre, using an iron fireplace poker; Elves and their powers are severely weakened by iron.  The witches bring Diamanda and the Elf to Lancre Castle, where Magrat treats Diamanda and Verence agrees to imprison the Elf (though Magrat inadvertently frees it later).  Meanwhile, Granny has begun to experience memories of other paths her life has taken in parallel worlds, as well as a growing sense of her own impending death.\n\n[[Jason Ogg]] and the other Lancre Morris Men plan a play to be performed for the wedding guests.  When they rehearse near the Dancers, the Elves influence them to include Elvish elements in the play.  As a result, when the play is performed at the Dancers, it causes sufficient belief\u2014a powerful force on the Discworld\u2014that the Elves are able to make the guests dismantle the stone circle. The Elves arrive, and the Elf Queen plans to legitimize her rule of Lancre by marrying Verence.  None of the members of the Lancre coven are present at this time: Magrat has locked herself in her room due to perceived insults in a letter she has discovered, written by Granny to Verence, advising him to plan the wedding; Nanny is being romanced by Casanunda; and Granny has been magically whisked away by Ridcully, who hopes to resume a romantic connection they had when much younger.  The women only become aware of what has happened once the Elves begin to wreak havoc in Lancre.  Aided only by general [[Dogsbody|dogsbody]] [[Shawn Ogg]], Magrat fights her way though the infiltrated castle.  She discovers a portrait of Queen Ynci, one of the kingdom's legendary founders.  Suddenly inspired by the idea of becoming a ''warrior ''queen, Magrat finds and dons Ynci's [[armour]].  Feeling influenced by Ynci's spirit (and unaware that Ynci is a fiction, the armour constructed from cookware only a few generations previously), she rescues a captured Shawn and sets out for the Dancers.  While Granny and Ridcully make their way through the woods, resulting in Granny's capture by the Elves, Nanny and Casanunda travel through a gateway to the abode of the Elf King, who opposes the Elf Queen despite being her spouse.\n\nAt the Dancers, Magrat arrives to confront the Elf Queen at the same time as the people of Lancre, rallied by Shawn and Nanny.  But the Elf Queen quickly subdues Magrat with glamour.  The captive Granny mentally combats the Elf Queen and releases Magrat from the glamour before succumbing to the Elf Queen's attack, her prone body being covered by the bees from her hive, which have swarmed at the Dancers.  When the Elf Queen turns her powers on Magrat, attempting to stop her resistance by dismantling her identity, she exposes the unexpectedly valorous core of Magrat's being, (something which Granny had deliberately been stoking, aggravating and provoking all along for just this very outcome).  Magrat attacks and subdues the Elf Queen just in time for a projection of the Elf King to arrive and send the Elves back to their world.\n\nGranny appears to be dead, but then Nanny and Magrat learn that she has actually borrowed her bees' hive mind; a feat thought impossible.  They break open a window in the castle, where Ridcully has reverently laid Granny's body, enabling the bees to get close enough for her to regain consciousness.  Nanny points out to Magrat that Granny's letter to Verence has had a great positive impact on Magrat's life, as well as giving her the strength to fight the Elf Queen.  Magrat and Verence are married by Ridcully.  Later, Granny and Ridcully make peace with their past and their place in the universe.  The growing sense of impending death she had been feeling had been due to the impending deaths of some of her parallel-selves.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Discworld#Lords and Ladies|Lords and Ladies}}\n* {{isfdb title|272}}\n*[http://www.lspace.org/books/apf/lords-and-ladies.html Annotations at the L-Space Web]\n*[http://www.lspace.org/books/pqf/lords-and-ladies.html Quotations]\n* [http://www.lspace.org/books/synopses/lords-and-ladies.html Synopsis]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[Discworld reading order|Reading order guide]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Small Gods]]| title = 14th [[Discworld#Novels|Discworld Novel]]  | years= | after = [[Men at Arms]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Witches Abroad]]| title = 4th [[Witches (Discworld)|Witches Story]]  | years=Published in 1992  | after = [[Maskerade]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Discworld books}}\n{{Terry Pratchett}}\n{{A Midsummer Night's Dream}}\n\n[[Category:1992 British novels]]\n[[Category:Discworld books]]\n[[Category:1992 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Novels about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Elves in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Works based on A Midsummer Night's Dream]]\n[[Category:Novels based on plays]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lords_and_Ladies_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Rydal railway station", "text_new": "<!-- Article title: Rydal railway station SHRNo:1239 DatabaseNo:5012211 -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{About|railway station in [[New South Wales]]|railway station in [[Pennsylvania]]|Rydal (SEPTA station)}}\n{{Infobox station\n|name                = Rydal\n|type                = \n|style               = NSW TrainLink regional \n|image               = XP2002_leads_WT28.jpg\n|image_size          = \n|image_caption       = [[NSW TrainLink]] [[New South Wales XPT|XPT]] at the station in December 2013\n|address             = Bathurst Street, [[Rydal, New South Wales|Rydal]]\n|country             = \n|coordinates         = {{coord|-33.4836|150.0318|region:AU-NSW_type:railwaystation|format=dms|display=inline,title}} \n| map_type            = Australia New South Wales\n| map_overlay         = <!-- Overlay image file name, to be placed on top of the main map. Should have the same border coordinates. -->\n| AlternativeMap      = <!-- Alternative map file name (changes background map, border coordinates are determined based on the map name); this is only recommended for use in templates. -->\n| map_alt             = <!-- Alternative text for map image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| map_caption         = <!-- Map caption; for no caption leave it blank; if the parameter is omitted then the caption will be \"Marker text (location map name)\" -->\n| map_size            = <!-- Width of map -->\n| map_dot_label       = <!-- Text to be displayed next to dot on map image -->\n| map_label_position  = \n|elevation           = \n|distance            = <!-- {{convert|111|mile}} allow for glenbrook and 10 tunnels deviations -->{{convert|181.4|km}} from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central]]\n|line                = [[Main Western railway line|Main Western]]\n|other               = \n|structure           = Ground\n|platform            = 2 side (1 disused)\n|depth               = \n|levels              = \n|tracks              = 1\n|parking             = \n|bicycle             = \n|opened              = 1 July 1870\n|closed              = \n|rebuilt             = \n|electrified         = \n|disabled            = Yes\n|code                = [[List of New South Wales railway station codes|RDL]]\n|owned               = [[RailCorp]]\n|operator            = [[NSW TrainLink]]\n|zone                = \n|former              = \n|passengers          = \n|pass_year           = \n|pass_percent        = \n|pass_system         = \n|mpassengers         = \n|services            = \n{{s-rail|title=NSW TrainLink}}\n{{s-line|system=NSW TrainLink intercity|line=Blue Mountains|previous=Lithgow|next=Tarana|notemid=(4 services daily) Bathurst Bullet}}\n{{s-line|system=NSW TrainLink|line=Western|previous=Tarana|next=Lithgow|branch=Dubbo XPT}}\n|web                 = \n|route_map           = \n|map_state           = \n| embedded =\n{{Infobox designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = Rydal Railway Station group\n| designation1_type = State heritage (complex / group)\n| designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1239\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Railway Platform/ Station\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n| designation1_free3name = Builders\n| designation1_free3value =\n}}\n}}\n'''Rydal railway station''' is a heritage-listed [[railway station]] located on the [[Main Western railway line, New South Wales|Main Western line]] in [[Rydal, New South Wales|Rydal]], [[City of Lithgow]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. It is also known as '''Rydal Railway Station group'''. The property is owned by [[RailCorp]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1239>{{cite NSW SHR|5012211|Rydal Railway Station group|hr=01239|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe station opened on 1 July 1870<ref>[http://www.nswrail.net/locations/show.php?name=NSW:Rydal Rydal Station] NSWrail.net</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13207620 |title=RAILWAY EXTENSION TO RYDAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=10,020 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 July 1870 |accessdate=26 March 2017 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and was the next finished extension west from [[Lithgow railway station|Lithgow]] after [[Wallerawang railway station|Wallerawang]] had been finalised four months earlier. Two years later the line was again extended finishing at {{NSWcity|Tarana}} before reaching {{StnlnkA|Bathurst|N}} in 1876.\n\nOn 14 March 1915, the line was duplicated with a second platform built. The station closed on 27 May 1989, with the track lifted from the 1915 built platform in 1998 when the line was singled.<ref>\"Western Stations Close\" ''[[Railway Digest]]'' August 1989 page 270</ref><ref>[http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4801331 Rydal Railway Station] NSW Environment & Heritage</ref>\n\nThe station building has been converted to a library.\n\n== Description ==\nThe complex comprises:<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n*Station / residence - type 1 - sub-type 2, 1869\n*Signal box - type 3, small, {{circa|1914}}<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n*Platform faces - stone and brick\n*War memorial\n\n==Services==\nRydal is served by [[NSW TrainLink]]'s daily ''[[Central West Express|Central West]] [[New South Wales XPT|XPT]]'' service operating between [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney]] and {{StnlnkA|Dubbo}}.<ref name=WesternTimetable>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Western Region}}</ref>  The XPT only stops on request if passengers have booked to board/alight here. From 16 September 2019 the 4 times daily ''[[Bathurst Bullet]]'' also stops here.<ref name=BlueMountainsTimetable>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Blue Mountains}}</ref><ref>[https://www.westernadvocate.com.au/story/6358039/villages-pleased-that-both-bullets-will-now-be-stopping/ Villages pleased that both Bullets will now be stopping] Western Advocate 30 August 2019</ref>\n\n{{Sydney Trains platform box\n|p1alinename       = Blue Mountains Line\n|p1astop           = 2 morning services to [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney Central]]<br/>2 evening services to [[Lithgow railway station|Lithgow]]<br/>4 daily services to [[Bathurst railway station, New South Wales|Bathurst]]\n|p1anotes          = <ref name=BlueMountainsTimetable/>\n|p1blinename       = NSW Trainlink Western\n|p1bstop           = Services to Sydney Central and Dubbo\n|p1bnotes          = request stop (booked passengers only)<ref name=WesternTimetable/>\n|p2alinename       = Not in use\n|p2astop           =\n|p2anotes          = }}\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 27 November 2000, the station building was constructed when the line opened to Rydal and retains its original form from that period. It is an important early railway complex that maintains its setting (largely through main road bypass) and which forms an important visual element in the valley viewed from both road approaches and from the level crossing. The changing view of the structure from the road is the visual focus of the town which is now a remnant of its previous importance as a centre for the production of fine wool.\nThe station building symbolises the confidence in railway construction and the transition towards a railway architecture. It is a rare example of a combined station/residence, five of which remain. All similar structures, found further west towards [[Blayney, New South Wales|Blayney]], have major alteration or extensions.\nThe other items on the site are significant as they indicate the development of the system and how early sites adapted to duplication and increased traffic followed by more recently decreased traffic.<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n\nRydal railway station was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThis item is assessed as historically rare. This item is assessed as scientifically rare. This item is assessed as arch. rare. This item is assessed as socially rare.<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Railways}}}}\n*[[:Category:Regional railway stations in New South Wales|List of railway stations in regional New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|author=Attraction Homepage|date=2007|title=Rydal Railway Station group|url=http://www.rydalmount.com.au/rydalstation.html}}\n=== Attribution ===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Rydal Railway Station group|dno=5012211|id=01239|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Rydal railway station}}\n*[https://transportnsw.info/stop?q=10155052#/ Rydal station details] Transport for New South Wales\n\n{{City of Lithgow topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Transport for New South Wales railway stations|Western Region=y|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Easy Access railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1870]]\n[[Category:Regional railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Rydal, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Houses in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Hotels in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Article title: Rydal railway station SHRNo:1239 DatabaseNo:5012211 -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{About|railway station in [[New South Wales]]|railway station in [[Pennsylvania]]|Rydal (SEPTA station)}}\n{{Infobox station\n|name                = Rydal\n|type                = \n|style               = NSW TrainLink regional \n|image               = XP2002_leads_WT28.jpg\n|image_size          = \n|image_caption       = [[NSW TrainLink]] [[New South Wales XPT|XPT]] at the station in December 2013\n|address             = Bathurst Street, [[Rydal, New South Wales|Rydal]]\n|country             = \n|coordinates         = {{coord|-33.4836|150.0318|region:AU-NSW_type:railwaystation|format=dms|display=inline,title}} \n| map_type            = Australia New South Wales\n| map_overlay         = <!-- Overlay image file name, to be placed on top of the main map. Should have the same border coordinates. -->\n| AlternativeMap      = <!-- Alternative map file name (changes background map, border coordinates are determined based on the map name); this is only recommended for use in templates. -->\n| map_alt             = <!-- Alternative text for map image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| map_caption         = <!-- Map caption; for no caption leave it blank; if the parameter is omitted then the caption will be \"Marker text (location map name)\" -->\n| map_size            = <!-- Width of map -->\n| map_dot_label       = <!-- Text to be displayed next to dot on map image -->\n| map_label_position  = \n|elevation           = \n|distance            = <!-- {{convert|111|mile}} allow for glenbrook and 10 tunnels deviations -->{{convert|181.4|km}} from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central]]\n|line                = [[Main Western railway line|Main Western]]\n|other               = \n|structure           = Ground\n|platform            = 2 side (1 disused)\n|depth               = \n|levels              = \n|tracks              = 1\n|parking             = \n|bicycle             = \n|opened              = 1 July 1870\n|closed              = \n|rebuilt             = \n|electrified         = \n|disabled            = Yes\n|code                = [[List of New South Wales railway station codes|RDL]]\n|owned               = [[RailCorp]]\n|operator            = [[NSW TrainLink]]\n|zone                = \n|former              = \n|passengers          = \n|pass_year           = \n|pass_percent        = \n|pass_system         = \n|mpassengers         = \n|services            = \n{{s-rail|title=NSW TrainLink}}\n{{s-line|system=NSW TrainLink intercity|line=Blue Mountains|previous=Lithgow|next=Tarana|notemid=(4 services daily) Bathurst Bullet}}\n{{s-line|system=NSW TrainLink|line=Western|previous=Tarana|next=Lithgow|branch=Dubbo XPT}}\n|web                 = \n|route_map           = \n|map_state           = \n| embedded =\n{{Infobox designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = Rydal Railway Station group\n| designation1_type = State heritage (complex / group)\n| designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1239\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Railway Platform/ Station\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n| designation1_free3name = Builders\n| designation1_free3value =\n}}\n}}\nThe '''Rydal railway station''' is a heritage-listed [[railway station]] located on the [[Main Western railway line, New South Wales|Main Western line]] in [[Rydal, New South Wales|Rydal]], [[City of Lithgow]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. It is also known as '''Rydal Railway Station group'''. The property is owned by [[RailCorp]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1239>{{cite NSW SHR|5012211|Rydal Railway Station group|hr=01239|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe station opened on 1 July 1870<ref>[http://www.nswrail.net/locations/show.php?name=NSW:Rydal Rydal Station] NSWrail.net</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13207620 |title=RAILWAY EXTENSION TO RYDAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=10,020 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 July 1870 |accessdate=26 March 2017 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and was the next finished extension west from [[Lithgow railway station|Lithgow]] after [[Wallerawang railway station|Wallerawang]] had been finalised four months earlier. Two years later the line was again extended finishing at {{NSWcity|Tarana}} before reaching {{StnlnkA|Bathurst|N}} in 1876.\n\nOn 14 March 1915, the line was duplicated with a second platform built. The station closed on 27 May 1989, with the track lifted from the 1915 built platform in 1998 when the line was singled.<ref>\"Western Stations Close\" ''[[Railway Digest]]'' August 1989 page 270</ref><ref>[http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4801331 Rydal Railway Station] NSW Environment & Heritage</ref>\n\nThe station building has been converted to a library.\n\n== Description ==\nThe complex comprises:<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n*Station / residence - type 1 - sub-type 2, 1869\n*Signal box - type 3, small, {{circa|1914}}<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n*Platform faces - stone and brick\n*War memorial\n\n==Services==\nRydal is served by [[NSW TrainLink]]'s daily ''[[Central West Express|Central West]] [[New South Wales XPT|XPT]]'' service operating between [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney]] and {{StnlnkA|Dubbo}}.<ref name=WesternTimetable>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Western Region}}</ref>  The XPT only stops on request if passengers have booked to board/alight here. From 16 September 2019 the 4 times daily ''[[Bathurst Bullet]]'' also stops here.<ref name=BlueMountainsTimetable>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Blue Mountains}}</ref><ref>[https://www.westernadvocate.com.au/story/6358039/villages-pleased-that-both-bullets-will-now-be-stopping/ Villages pleased that both Bullets will now be stopping] Western Advocate 30 August 2019</ref>\n\n{{Sydney Trains platform box\n|p1alinename       = Blue Mountains Line\n|p1astop           = 2 morning services to [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney Central]]<br/>2 evening services to [[Lithgow railway station|Lithgow]]<br/>4 daily services to [[Bathurst railway station, New South Wales|Bathurst]]\n|p1anotes          = <ref name=BlueMountainsTimetable/>\n|p1blinename       = NSW Trainlink Western\n|p1bstop           = Services to Sydney Central and Dubbo\n|p1bnotes          = request stop (booked passengers only)<ref name=WesternTimetable/>\n|p2alinename       = Not in use\n|p2astop           =\n|p2anotes          = }}\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 27 November 2000, the station building was constructed when the line opened to Rydal and retains its original form from that period. It is an important early railway complex that maintains its setting (largely through main road bypass) and which forms an important visual element in the valley viewed from both road approaches and from the level crossing. The changing view of the structure from the road is the visual focus of the town which is now a remnant of its previous importance as a centre for the production of fine wool.\nThe station building symbolises the confidence in railway construction and the transition towards a railway architecture. It is a rare example of a combined station/residence, five of which remain. All similar structures, found further west towards [[Blayney, New South Wales|Blayney]], have major alteration or extensions.\nThe other items on the site are significant as they indicate the development of the system and how early sites adapted to duplication and increased traffic followed by more recently decreased traffic.<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n\nRydal railway station was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThis item is assessed as historically rare. This item is assessed as scientifically rare. This item is assessed as arch. rare. This item is assessed as socially rare.<ref name=nswshr-1239/>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Railways}}}}\n*[[:Category:Regional railway stations in New South Wales|List of railway stations in regional New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|author=Attraction Homepage|date=2007|title=Rydal Railway Station group|url=http://www.rydalmount.com.au/rydalstation.html}}\n=== Attribution ===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Rydal Railway Station group|dno=5012211|id=01239|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Rydal railway station}}\n*[https://transportnsw.info/stop?q=10155052#/ Rydal station details] Transport for New South Wales\n\n{{City of Lithgow topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Transport for New South Wales railway stations|Western Region=y|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Easy Access railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1870]]\n[[Category:Regional railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Rydal, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Houses in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Hotels in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "name_user": "Fork99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed 'the' as starting word as 'Rydal... station' is a singular noun", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rydal_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Park Geun-hye", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Eleventh President of South Korea}}\n{{Korean name|Park}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Excellency|Her Excellency]]\n| name = Park Geun-hye\n| office = 11th [[President of South Korea]]\n| native_name = {{nobold|\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c(\u6734\u69ff\u60e0)}}\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| image = File:Korea President Park UN 20130506 01 cropped.jpg\n| predecessor = [[Lee Myung-bak]]\n| primeminister = [[Chung Hong-won]]<br />[[Lee Wan-koo]]<br />[[Choi Kyoung-hwan]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]\n| successor = [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Moon Jae-in]]\n| signature = Park Geun-hye signature.svg\n| predecessor2 = Choe Byeong-ryeol\n| party = [[Liberty Korea Party|Liberty Korea]] (1997\u20132017)<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (2017\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/politics/2017/11/03/0502000000AKR20171103139800001.HTML?template=2085 |title=\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9, '1\ud638 \ub2f9\uc6d0' \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ucd9c\ub2f9\uc870\uce58\u2026'20\ub144 \uad00\uacc4' \uccad\uc0b0 |newspaper=Yonhap News |date=3 November 2017 |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n| office1 = Leader of the [[Liberty Korea Party]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Hwang Woo-yea]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n| successor1 = [[Hwang Woo-yea]]\n| successor2 = Kim Yeong-seon {{small|(Acting)}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|02|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Daegu|Taegu]], [[First Republic of Korea|South Korea]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| parents = [[Park Chung-hee]]<br />[[Yuk Young-soo]]\n| alma_mater = [[Sogang University]]<br />[[Universit\u00e9 Grenoble Alpes]]\n| term_start = 25 February 2013\n| term_end = 10 March 2017{{efn|name=note|Her powers and duties suspended since 9 December 2016 by the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] until final impeachment verdict on 10 March 2017}}\n| term_start1 = 19 December 2011\n| term_end1 = 15 May 2012\n| term_start2 = 23 March 2004\n| term_end2 = 15 June 2006\n| office3 = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| term_start3 = 30 May 2012\n| term_end3 = 10 December 2012\n| constituency3 = {{nowrap|[[List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2012\u20132016|Proportional representation]]}}\n| term_start4 = 3 April 1998\n| term_end4 = 29 May 2012\n| constituency4 = [[Dalseong County|Dalseong]] ([[Daegu]])\n| predecessor4 = Kim Suk-won\n| successor4 = Lee Jong-jin\n| office5 = [[First Lady of South Korea]]<br />{{small|Acting}}\n| president5 = [[Park Chung-hee]]\n| residence = [[Seoul]]\n| term_label5 = In role\n| term_start5 = 16 August 1974\n| term_end5 = 26 October 1979\n| predecessor5 = [[Yuk Young-soo]]\n| successor5 = [[Hong Gi]]\n| module = {{Infobox Korean name\n|child            = yes\n|hangul           = {{linktext|\ubc15|\uadfc|\ud61c}}\n|hanja            = {{lang|ko|{{linktext|\u6734|\u69ff|\u60e0}}}}\n|rr               = Bak Geun(-)hye\n|mr               = Pak K\u016dnhye}}\n}}\n'''Park Geun-hye''' ({{Korean|\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c|hanja=\u6734\u69ff\u60e0|rr=Bak Geun(-)hye}}; {{IPA-ko|pak\u203fk\u0348\u026fn.hje|IPA}}; often in English {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u0251r|k|_|\u02cc|g|\u028a|n|_|\u02c8|h|e\u026a}}; born 2 February 1952) is a South Korean former  [[politician]] who served as [[President of South Korea]] from 2013 to 2017. Park was the first woman to be [[List of Presidents of South Korea|President of South Korea]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/19/world/la-fg-south-korea-park-20121220 |title=South Korea elects first female president |last=Demick |first=Barbara |date=19 December 2012 |last2=Choi |first2=Jung-yoon|newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035 |access-date=18 November 2016}}</ref> and also the first female president [[List of elected and appointed female heads of state and government|popularly elected as head of state]] in [[East Asia]]. She was also the first South Korean president to be born after the founding of [[First Republic of Korea]]; her predecessors were born either during the [[Joseon|Joseon dynasty]], [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]] or during the [[United States Army Military Government in Korea|post-World War II American occupation]]. Her father, [[Park Chung-hee]], was the [[President of South Korea]] from 1963 to 1979, serving five consecutive terms after he [[May 16 coup|seized power in 1961]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nBefore her presidency, Park was chairwoman of the conservative Grand National Party (GNP, formerly called the [[Saenuri Party (2017)|Saenuri Party]] from February 2012 onwards now called the [[Liberty Korea Party]]) from 2004 to 2006 and 2011 to 2012. She was also a member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]], serving four consecutive parliamentary terms between 1998 and 2012. She started her fifth term as a representative elected via [[Party-list proportional representation|national list]] in June 2012. In 2013 and 2014, Park ranked 11th on the [[Forbes list of The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|''Forbes'' list of the world's 100 most powerful women]] and the most powerful woman in East Asia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/lmh45lfdj/geun-hye-park/ |title=The 25 Most Powerful Women in the World |accessdate=16 June 2014 |work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> In 2014, she ranked 46th on the [[Forbes list of The World's Most Powerful People|''Forbes'' list of the world's most powerful people]], the third-highest [[South Korea]]n on the list, after [[Lee Kun-hee]] and [[Lee Jae-yong (businessman)|Lee Jae-yong]].\n\nOn 9 December 2016, [[Impeachment of Park Geun-hye|the National Assembly impeached Park]] on charges related to [[influence peddling]] by her top aide, [[Choi Soon-sil]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/09/world/asia/south-korea-president-park-geun-hye-impeached.html |title=South Korea Parliament Votes to Impeach President Park Geun-hye|date=9 December 2016| work=[[The New York Times]] |author=Choe Sang-hun |accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> Then-[[Prime Minister of South Korea|Prime Minister]] [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] assumed her powers and duties as Acting President as a result.<ref name=\"Yonhap\">{{Cite web |url= http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2015/05/21/0301000000AEN20150521002600315.html |title=Park names Justice Minister Hwang Kyo-ahn as new PM |date=21 May 2015 |publisher=[[Yonhap]] |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref> The [[Constitutional Court of Korea|Constitutional Court]] upheld the impeachment by a unanimous 8\u20130 ruling on 10 March 2017, thereby removing Park from office.<ref name=\"impeach0310nyt\">{{cite news|last1=Sang-hun|first1=Choe|title=South Korea Removes President Park Geun-hye|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/world/asia/park-geun-hye-impeached-south-korea.html|accessdate=10 March 2017|work=The New York Times|date=9 March 2017}}</ref> On 6 April 2018, South Korean courts sentenced Park to 24 years in prison which was later increased to 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-43666134|title=Park Geun-hye: South Korea's ex-leader jailed for 24 years for corruption|work=BBC News|date=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=25yearssentence>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southkorea-politics-park/south-korean-court-raises-ex-president-parks-jail-term-to-25-years-idUSKCN1L905P|title= South Korean court raises ex-president Park's jail term to 25 years|work=Reuters|date=24 August 2018}}</ref> Park is currently imprisoned at [[Seoul Detention Center]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/31/world/asia/park-geun-hye-arrest-jail-south-korea.html|title=Park Geun-hye's Life in Jail: Cheap Meals and a Mattress on the Floor|last=Sang-hun|first=Choe|date=31 March 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 May 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2018, two separate criminal cases resulted in an increase of seven years in prison for Park. Park was found guilty of illegally taking off-the-book funds from the [[National Intelligence Service (South Korea)|National Intelligence Service]]. This resulted in a five year prison sentence. In another case Park was found guilty of illegally interfering in the [[Saenuri Party]] primaries in the [[2016 South Korean legislative election]]. She was sentenced to two more years in prison.<ref>https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20190725010700315 . Retrieved 26 September 2019</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nPark was born on 2 February 1952, in Samdeok-dong of [[Jung District, Daegu]], as the first child of [[Park Chung-hee]], the unelected 3rd president of South Korea, who having come to power with the [[May 16 military coup d'\u00e9tat]] of 1961, served from 1963 until his assassination in 1979, and [[Yuk Young-soo]]. Both of her parents were assassinated. She has a younger brother, Park Ji-man, and a younger sister, Park Geun-ryeong.<ref>{{cite news |title=Candidacy of ruling party leader's sister gets cold shoulder |date=18 March 2012 |newspaper=The Korea Herald |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20120318000328}}</ref> She is unmarried with no children. [[Pew Research Center]] described her as an atheist with a Buddhist and Roman Catholic upbringing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2014/08/12/6-facts-about-christianity-in-south-korea/|title=6 facts about South Korea's growing Christian population|date=12 August 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Park's family moved to Seoul and she graduated from Seoul's Jangchung Elementary School and Sungshim (literal: Sacred Heart) Girls' Middle and High School in 1970, going on to receive a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[electronic engineering]] from [[Sogang University]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite news |title=(profile)Hannara Party Vice Chairwoman, Park Geun-hye |date=31 May 2000 |publisher=YONHAP NEWS AGENCY |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=001&aid=0000006171}}</ref> She briefly studied at [[Joseph Fourier University]], but left France following the murder of her mother.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harlan |first=Chico |date=25 January 2013 |title=South Korea's new leader, Park Geun-hye, was pushed onto political stage by tragedy |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/for-s-koreas-park-after-tragedy-a-first-taste-of-power/2013/01/25/0dc9382e-5e30-11e2-90a0-73c8343c6d61_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nPark's mother was killed on 15 August 1974 in the [[National Theater of Korea]]; [[Mun Se-gwang]], a [[Koreans in Japan|Japanese-born ethnic Korean]] sympathizer of [[North Korea]] and member of the [[Chongryon]], was attempting to assassinate President Park Chung-hee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://100.naver.com/100.nhn?docid=180730|script-title=ko:8\u00b715\ub300\ud1b5\ub839\uc800\uaca9\uc0ac\uac74 (\u516b\u4e00\u4e94\u5927\u7d71\u9818\u72d9\u64ca\u4e8b\u4ef6) |trans-title=15 August President assassination-attempt incident|publisher= Doopedia (\ub450\uc0b0\ubc31\uacfc)|accessdate=13 May 2012|language=Korean}}</ref> Park was regarded as [[First Lady]] until the [[assassination of Park Chung-hee|assassination of her father]] by his own intelligence chief, [[Kim Jae-gyu]], on 26 October 1979.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: South Korean President Park Geun-hye|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-20787271|accessdate=3 January 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|date=10 March 2017|quote=Some said the association with her father \u2013 and her experience as first lady \u2013 helped cement her win by overcoming prejudices among male voters.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://belfercenter.hks.harvard.edu/files/kogan-apsa-aug-2013.pdf|title=Weiner, Tim: ''Legacy of Ashes. The History of CIA''. New York, June 2007.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Weiner, Tim: ''Legacy of Ashes. The History of CIA''. New York, June 2007.|isbn = 978-0307389008|last1 = Weiner|first1 = Tim|year = 2008}}</ref> During this time, activists who were political opponents of her father claimed to be subject to arbitrary detention. Further, [[human rights in South Korea|human rights]] were considered subordinate to [[economy of South Korea|economic development]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=C. I. Eugene Kim|title=Emergency, Development, and Human Rights: South Korea| journal=Asian Survey| date=April 1978 |volume= 18|issue= 4|pages=363\u201378|doi=10.1525/as.1978.18.4.01p0404m|jstor=2643400}}</ref> In 2007, Park expressed regret at the treatment of activists during this period.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.kbs.co.kr/news/newsview_sub.php?menu=2&key=2007071913|title=Park Calls 1961 Coup 'Revolution' to Save Nation|date=19 July 2009|accessdate=13 May 2012|work=[[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] news|quote=She apologized for the sufferings and sacrifices of pro-democracy activists under the constitutional system, which was effective between 1972 and 1979.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225182651/http://english.kbs.co.kr/news/newsview_sub.php?menu=2&key=2007071913|archivedate=25 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nPark received honorary doctoral degrees from the [[Chinese Culture University]] in [[Taiwan]] in 1987, [[Pukyong National University]] and [[KAIST]] in 2008, [[Sogang University]] in 2010, and [[TU Dresden]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tu-dresden.de/tu-dresden/newsportal/news/ep_park?set_language=en|title=TU Dresden awards President of the Republic of Korea, Park Geun-hye, honorary doctorate|last=|first=|date=31 March 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=15 June 2016}}</ref><!-- This belongs in honors or recognitions. -->\n\n== Political career ==\n=== Assemblywoman ===\nPark was elected a Grand National Party (GNP) assemblywoman for [[Dalseong County]], Daegu, in 1998 [[by-election]], and three more times in the same electoral district between 1998 and 2008, being the incumbent assemblywoman till April 2012. In 2012, she announced that she would not run for a constituency representative seat for the 19th election in Dalseong or anywhere else, but for a proportional representative position for the Saenuri Party instead, in order to lead the party's election campaign.<ref name=\"New Pres Dec 19 2012\" /> She was elected as a proportional representative in the [[2012 South Korean legislative election|April 2012 election]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Chung Min-uck |date=20 March 2013 |title=Saenuri names proportional representatives |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2012/03/116_107308.html |work=Korea Times |accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Fackler\">{{cite news |last=Fackler |first=Martin |date=20 April 2012 |title=In a Rowdy Democracy, a Dictator's Daughter With an Unsoiled Aura |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/21/world/asia/park-geun-hye-an-unsoiled-leader-in-south-koreas-rowdy-democracy.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== GNP chairwoman and \"Queen of Elections\" ===\nDue to the failed attempt to impeach President [[Roh Moo-hyun]] and the bribery scandal of its 2002 presidential candidate, [[Lee Hoi-chang]] (revealed in 2004), the GNP was facing a severe defeat in the 2004 general election. Park was appointed as the chairwoman of the party and led the election efforts. In the election, the GNP lost its majority position but managed to gain 121 seats, which is largely considered a great achievement under such inhospitable circumstances for the party.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=001&aid=0005579513 |title=\ucd1d\uc120 D-1 \uc2b9\ud328\uae30\uc900..\uc601\ub0a8\uc2b9\ubd80 \uad00\uc2ec |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://biz.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/04/08/2012040800451.html |title=[\uc99d\uc2dc\u9591\ub2f4] \ucd1d\uc120 \uacb0\uacfc\uc5d0 \ucd09\uac01 \uc138\uc6b0\ub294 \uc8fc\uc2dd\uc2dc\uc7a5 |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> As the chairwoman of the GNP, Park helped her party make significant gains in local elections and actually obtain a majority in 2006.\n\nDuring the campaign, on 20 May 2006, Ji Chung-ho, a 50-year-old man with eight criminal convictions, slashed Park's face with a utility knife, causing an 11-centimeter wound that required 60 stitches and several hours of surgery.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2006/05/22/2006052261007.html |title=Joint Probe into Attack on GNP Chairwoman |work=Arirang News |date=22 May 2006 |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=038&aid=0000330425 |script-title=ko:\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c\ub300\ud45c \uc720\uc138\uc7a5\uc11c \ud53c\uc2b5 \uc911\uc0c1 |trans-title=GNP leader Park Geun-hye attacked during campaign |date=21 May 2006 |accessdate=16 May 2012 |work=Hankook Ilbo |author1=Gim Yi-sak(\uae40\uc774\uc0ad) |author2=Chung Min-seung(\uc815\ubbfc\uc2b9) |language=Korean}}</ref> A famous anecdote from this incident occurred when Park was hospitalized after the attack. The first word that she said to her secretary after her recovery from her wound was \"How is [[Daejeon]]?\" After this, the candidate from the Grand National Party won the election for mayor of the city of Daejeon despite having trailed by more than 20 percentage points in opinion polls up to the point of the attack. In addition, during her term as the GNP chairwoman between 2004 and 2006, the party won all 40 reelections and by-elections held, which was largely credited to her influence and efforts. This feat gave Park a nickname \"Queen of Elections\".<ref name=\"2006 Maeil Kyongge article\">{{cite web|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=009&aid=0000506402|title=\ub300\uc804 \"\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \uc0dd\uac01\ud558\uba74 \uacb0\uc2ec\uc774 \ud754\ub4e4\ub824\uc694\"|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"2011 Yeonhap News article\">{{cite news |url= http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=001&aid=0005298622 |script-title=ko:\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c, \u91ce\uc2dc\uc808 `40\ub300 0 \uc2e0\ud654'.\uc774\ubc88\uc5d4?|trans-title=Park Geun-hye scored 40 to 0 as the opposition. How about this time? |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=16 May 2012 |work=[[Yonhap News]] |author=Kim Nam-kwon (\uae40\ub0a8\uad8c) |language=Korean}}</ref><ref name=\"2012 Newsis article\">{{cite news |url= http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=003&aid=0004415188 |script-title=ko:'\uc120\uac70\uc758 \uc5ec\uc655' \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c, \ucd1d\uc120\uc5d0\uc11c \ub4b7\uc2ec \ubc1c\ud718\ud560\uae4c? |trans-title='Queen of elections' Park Geun-hye, Could she wield her magic again in April? |date=29 March 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012 | language=Korean |work=NewsIs |author=Kim Min-ja(\uae40\ubbfc\uc790)}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February 2007, Park made a much-publicized visit to [[Harvard University]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], United States. Her visit culminated in an address to a packed audience at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], where she said she wanted to save Korea and advocated a stronger relationship between [[South Korea\u2013United States relations|South Korea and the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=516993 |title=Politician Wants To 'Save' Korea: South Korean National Assembly member advocates alliance with United States |date= 13 February 2007 |accessdate=16 May 2012 |work=The Harvard Crimson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icasinc.org/2007/2007l/2007lghp.html |title=The Republic of Korea and the United States:Our Future Together |date=21 February 2007 |accessdate=16 May 2012 |work=Institute for Corean-American Studies, Inc.|quote=An Address Delivered at the ARCO (John F. Kennedy Jr.) Forum, John F. Kennedy School of Government Harvard University}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007 Presidential bid ===\nPark hoped to emulate her father's success by becoming the presidential nominee of the Grand National Party.<ref name=\"NYT-Fackler\"/> She eventually lost to [[Lee Myung-bak]] by a narrow margin. Lee had a commanding lead at the beginning of the primary season, but Park was able to narrow the gap through allegations of Lee's corruption. Park won the \"party members' bid\", but she lost the \"national bid\", which is a larger percentage of the total presidential bid.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n=== 2008 general election ===\nAfter the [[2007 South Korean presidential election|2007 presidential election]], President Lee Myung-bak formed a government of mostly close supporters.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestyuopics/people/l/lee_myung_bak/index.html | title= Lee Myung-bak | work= The New York Times| date= 25 July 2012 | accessdate=13 November 2012}}</ref> Park's supporters argued that this was a kind of political reprisal, and that they should secede from the Grand National Party.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://spearheadresearch.org/SR_CMS/index.php/internationalaffairssecuirty/south-korea-park-likely-to-be-first-female-president | archive-url= https://archive.is/20130416011926/http://spearheadresearch.org/SR_CMS/index.php/internationalaffairssecuirty/south-korea-park-likely-to-be-first-female-president | url-status= dead | archive-date= 16 April 2013 | title= South Korea: Park Likely to be First Female President | work= Spearhead Research | date= 28 August 2012 | accessdate= 13 November 2012 }}</ref> Eventually, they formed parties named [[Pro-Park Coalition]] and Solidarity for Pro-Park Independents (\uce5c\ubc15 \ubb34\uc18c\uc18d \uc5f0\ub300; ''Chin Park Musosok Yeondae''). Park herself did not join them, but indirectly supported them by announcing \"I hope these people will come back alive.\" After the mass secession, the rebels announced that they would rejoin GNP after the general election, but the GNP prohibited it. In the following [[2008 South Korean legislative election|2008 general election]], the rebels won 26 seats: 14 from the Pro-Park Coalition and 12 as independents. Together, they played a pivotal role in the GNP's narrow majority. Park continually insisted that GNP should allow the return of her supporters. As of 2011, most of these rebels had returned to the GNP, resulting in approximately 50 to 60 assembly members who support Park out of 171 in the GNP.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n=== Head of Saenuri Party ===\nAs a response to the dwindling approval rating of the GNP, the party formed an emergency committee and changed the name of the political party from the Grand National Party to the ''Saenuri'' Party, meaning \"New Frontier\" Party.<ref name=\"New Pres Dec 19 2012\" /> On 19 December 2011, Park was appointed as the chairwoman of GNP's Emergency Committee, the [[de facto]] leader of the party.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n=== 2012 parliamentary election ===\nThe Saenuri Party achieved a surprise win against the opposing [[Democratic United Party]] in the 2012 General Election, winning 152 seats and retaining its majority position. Because of the corruption scandals of the Lee administration revealed before the election, the Saenuri Party was widely expected to win no more than 100 seats.<ref name=\"2012 Hankyoreh article\">{{cite news| url= http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/politics/politics_general/527972.html |script-title=ko:\u2018\uc120\uac70\uc758 \uc5ec\uc655\u2019 \ud654\ub824\ud55c \uadc0\ud658...\uc218\ub3c4\uad8c\u00b7\uc80a\uc740\uce35\uc5d0\uc120 \ud55c\uacc4 |trans-title=Return of Queen of election. Park also showed her limit among capital area voters and the youth |date=12 April 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012 |work=[[The Hankyoreh]] |language=Korean |author=Sung Yeon-chul(\uc131\uc5f0\ucca0)}}</ref> During the 13-day campaign period, Park traveled about {{cvt| 7200|km|mi }} around South Korea, visiting more than 100 constituencies.<ref name=\"2012 Joongang Ilbo article\">{{cite news|url=http://article.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=7895558&ctg=1000 |script-title=ko:'\uccad\ubc14\uc9c0 \uc720\uc138' \uace0\uac1c \ud754\ub4e4\ub358 \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c, 30\ubd84 \ub4a4 |trans-title=Park Geun-hye shook head for wearing jeans, but after 30 minutes changed her mind |date=14 April 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012 |language=Korean |work=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |author1=Kim Jeong-ha(\uae40\uc815\ud558) |author2=Hur Jin(\ud5c8\uc9c4) |author3=Sohn Guk-hee(\uc190\uad6d\ud76c) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523105824/http://article.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=7895558&ctg=1000 |archivedate=23 May 2013 }}</ref> It is the consensus of Korean news media and political experts that the most important factor leading to Saenuri Party's victory was Park's leadership. For this reason, the 2012 election was often dubbed the \"return of the Queen of Election\".<ref name=\"2012 Hankyoreh article\" /><ref name=\"2012 edaily article\">{{cite news|url=http://www.edaily.co.kr/news/NewsRead.edy?SCD=DA32&newsid=01787606596478848&DCD=A01503&OutLnkChk=Y|script-title=ko:'\uc5ec\uc655\uc758 \ud654\ub824\ud55c \uadc0\ud658' \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c\uac00 \ub3cc\uc544\uc654\ub2e4|trans-title=Return of Queen of election, Park Geun-hye returned as GNP leader|date=15 December 2011|accessdate=16 May 2012|language=Korean|author=Kim Sung-gon(\uae40\uc131\uace4)|work=Edaily News}}</ref> Saenuri's defeat in the populous Seoul metropolitan area in this election, however, revealed the limitation of Park's political influence.<ref name=\"2012 Hankyoreh article\" />\n\n=== 2012 presidential campaign ===\n{{Main|2012 South Korean presidential election}}\nPark had been the leading candidate for the [[2012 South Korean presidential election|2012 presidential election]] in every national-level poll in South Korea between 2008, when the Lee Myung-bak administration began, and September 2011, with an approval rating of 25% to 45%, more than twice that of the second candidate. Park's approval rating was highest when the 2008 National Assembly election showed her strong influence and lowest in early 2010 as a result of her political stance against the Lee administration in [[Sejong City]] issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=001&aid=0005258502| script-title=ko:\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ub300\uc138\ub860 `\ud718\uccad'..\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c \ubcc0\ud654 \ubaa8\uc0c9|trans-title=Park Geun-hye's top candidate position is challenged. needs to change her style|date=8 September 2011|accessdate=16 May 2012|work=[[Yonhap News]]|author=Kim Hwa-young(\uae40\ud654\uc601)|language=Korean|quote=Faced with rising [[Ahn Cheol-soo]]'s approval rate, Park Geun-hye's leadership is in question. Sending messages wouldn't be enough, and she must increase her appearance in public. Park will try to tackle the center. [\u5b89\u98a8\uc5d0 \ub300\uc138\ub860 \uc81c\ub3d9 \uac78\ub824..\uc815\uce58\uc801 \uc2dc\ud5d8\ub300 \uc62c\ub77c. `\uba54\uc2dc\uc9c0 \uc815\uce58'\uc11c `\ud604\uc7a5\uc815\uce58'\ub85c..\uc911\ub3c4\uce35 \uacf5\ub7b5 \ubcf8\uaca9\ud654 \uc608\uc0c1]}}</ref> Park also benefited from a public image of standing aloofly above the fray of politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/21/world/asia/park-geun-hye-an-unsoiled-leader-in-south-koreas-rowdy-democracy.html?searchResultPosition=4|title=In a Rowdy Democracy, a Dictator's Daughter With an Unsoiled Aura|last=Fackler|first=Martin|date=20 April 2012|website=[[The New York Times]]|language=en|access-date=13 July 2019}}</ref>\nIn September 2011, [[Ahn Cheol-soo]], a former venture IT&nbsp;businessman and the Dean of Graduate School of Convergence Science and Technology at [[Seoul National University]], emerged as a strong independent candidate for the presidency. In national-level presidential polls in September 2011, Ahn and Park Geun Hye closely competed for the status of front-runner, with Park losing the top seat in some polls for the first time since 2008.<ref name=\"news.naver.com\">{{cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=001&aid=0005260480|script-title=ko:\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c-\uc548\ucca0\uc218, \uc5ec\ub860\uc870\uc0ac `\uc5ce\uce58\ub77d\ub4a4\uce58\ub77d'|trans-title=Poll: Park Geun-hye and An Cheol-soo are in fierce competition|date=10 September 2011|accessdate=16 May 2012|language=Korean|work=[[Yonhap News]]|author=Kim Nam-kwon(\uae40\ub0a8\uad8c)|quote=All eyes on public opinion after [[Chuseok]] holiday. [\ucd94\uc11d \uc5f0\ud734 \uc9c1\ud6c4 `\ubbfc\uc2ec \ud5a5\ubc30'\uc5d0 \uc774\ubaa9 \uc9d1\uc911]}}</ref>\n\nAfter her victory in the 2012 General Election, Park's approval rating increased significantly. In a national-level survey by Mono Research on 30 August<ref>[http://www.kmobile.co.kr/k_mnews/news/news_view.asp?tableid=IT&idx=405228 \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ucee8\ubca4\uc158 \ud6a8\uacfc...\uc548\ucca0\uc218 \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728\ub3c4 \ub3d9\ubc18\uc0c1\uc2b9] in 2012, {{in lang|ko}}</ref> Park was the top presidential candidate with an approval rating of 45.5% when competing with all potential candidates, and according to another recent national survey result, had a higher approval rating (50.6%) than Ahn (43.9%) in a two-way competition with him as of 11 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joongang.joinsmsn.com/article/936/9313936.html?ctg=1000&joongang|title=home survey 2012 survey by Realmeter|publisher=joongang.joinsmsn.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130126211012/http://joongang.joinsmsn.com/article/936/9313936.html?ctg=1000&joongang|archivedate=26 January 2013}}</ref>\nOn 10 July, Park formally announced her 2012 presidential bid at the Time Square, [[Yeongdeungpo District]], Seoul. In this event she emphasized the right to pursue happiness, a democratic economy, and customized welfare services for the Korean people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20120710/47651073/1|title=\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ub300\uc120 \ucd9c\ub9c8\uc120\uc5b8\u2026\ub300\uc120\ub808\uc774\uc2a4 \ubcf8\uaca9 \uc810\ud654|publisher=news.donga.com|date=10 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe opposing Democratic Party elected [[Moon Jae-in]] as its presidential candidate on 17 September, while Ahn Cheol-soo announced his presidential bid on 19 September. Although still a leading candidate, Park had a lower approval rating than both Ahn and Moon when engaged in two-way competition, according to a 22 September national survey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joongang.joinsmsn.com/article/367/9398367.html?ctg=1000&joongang|title=home survey 2012 survey by Realmeter|publisher=joongang.joinsmsn.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130126235525/http://joongang.joinsmsn.com/article/367/9398367.html?ctg=1000&joongang|archivedate=26 January 2013}}</ref> She was elected as the President of the Republic of Korea on 19 December 2012 with the approval of 51.6% of Korean voters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harlan |first=Chico |date=19 December 2012 |title=Park Geun-hye wins South Korea's presidential election |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/park-geun-hye-leads-in-south-koreas-presidential-election/2012/12/19/783398d4-49e6-11e2-b6f0-e851e741d196_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the NSI admitted that it had conducted an illicit campaign to influence the 2012 presidential election, mobilising teams of experts in psychological warfare to ensure that the conservative candidate, Park Geun-hye, beat her liberal rival [[Moon Jae-in]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/aug/04/south-koreas-spy-agency-admits-trying-rig-election-national-intelligence-service-2012|title=South Korea spy agency admits trying to rig 2012 presidential election|first=Justin|last=McCurry|date=4 August 2017|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=== Positions ===\n[[File:KOCIS CheongWaDae Children Day 02 (8713947728).jpg|thumb|President Park Geun-hye (center) smiles and shows a portrait drawn by a girl in Cheong Wa Dae, Seoul, at [[Children's Day]] 5 May 2013]]\nIn a 2012 survey by Korean Research assessing the political stance of 12 potential presidential candidates of South Korea, Park was considered the most conservative candidate.<ref name=\"New Pres Dec 19 2012\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hankooki.com/lpage/politics/201206/h2012060802354721000.htm |title=\ud55c\uad6d\uc544\uc774\ub2f7\ucef4! |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608101501/http://news.hankooki.com/lpage/politics/201206/h2012060802354721000.htm |archivedate= 8 June 2012 }}</ref> Her conservative, market-oriented political stance was well reflected in her campaign pledge for 2008 presidential bid to cut taxes, reduce regulation, and establish strong law and order.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2012&no=230947|title=2007\ub144, \uc904\ud478\uc138\u00b7\uc2dc\uc7a5\uc8fc\uc758 \u2192 2012\ub144, \ub9de\ucda4\ud615 \ubcf5\uc9c0\u00b7\uacbd\uc81c\ubbfc\uc8fc\ud654|publisher=}}</ref> Since 2009, however, Park started to focus more on welfare issues, advocating customized welfare services to the South Korean people.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nPark was well known for her strict adherence to political promises. In 2010, for example, she successfully stopped the Lee administration's attempt to cancel the plan to establish [[Sejong City]], a new national center of administration, arguing that the plan was a promise made to the people. This conflict between Park and the Lee Administration cost her a considerable decrease in her approval rating at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nanumnews.com/sub_read.html?uid=17379&section=sc201|title=[\ub098\ub214\ub274\uc2a4] \"\uc138\uc885\uc2dc \ud53c\ub85c\uac10\uc5d0 \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 \ud558\ub77d\uc138\"|publisher=nanumnews.com}}</ref> In 2012, Park also vowed to construct a new airport in the southeastern region, a 2008 presidential campaign promise made by GNP but cancelled in 2011, despite claims of economic infeasibility of the plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaeil.com/sub_news/sub_news_view.php?news_id=9929&yy=2012|title=2012 Maeil Sinmoon article|publisher=imaeil.com}}</ref>\n\nThe administrative vision of President Park Geun-hye's new government was \"a new era of hope and happiness\". The five Administrative Goals of the government were \"a jobs-centered creative economy\", \"tailored employment and welfare\", \"creativity-oriented education and cultural enrichment\", \"a safe and united society\" and \"strong security measures for sustainable peace on the Korean Peninsula\". The Park Geun-hye administration planned to create a trustworthy, clean, and capable government through carrying out these goals, related strategies, and tasks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.korea.net/Government/Current-Affairs/National-Affairs?affairId=346|title=Korea.net : The official website of the Republic of Korea|first=Korean Culture and Information Service|last=(KOCIS)|publisher=korea.net}}</ref>\n\nPark chose not to vote in the [[2017 South Korean presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170509000419 |newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]] |title=Did jailed ex-president Park Geun-hye use her vote? |date=9 May 2017 |access-date=13 May 2017 |first=Hyun-ju |last=Ock |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514025809/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170509000419 |archive-date=14 May 2017 |quote=According to local news reports, she gave up her right to vote as she did not ask for an absentee ballot, which is provided to inmates in detention facilities.}}</ref>\n\n== Presidency ==\n=== Inauguration ===\n[[File:Korea_18th_Presidential_Inaugural_06.jpg|thumb|President Park Geun-hye on inauguration day, 25 February 2013]]\nPark became the 18th president of South Korea on 25 February 2013. At midnight, she took over all presidential authorities including the prerogative of supreme command of South Korea's armed forces from her predecessor Lee Myung-bak. In her inauguration speech at the National Assembly building, Park spoke of her plan to open a new era of hope through \"economic prosperity, people's happiness, and cultural enrichment\". She particularly expressed her hope that North Korea would give up its nuclear arms and walk on the path of peace and mutual development, and declared that the foundation for a happy era of unification in which all Korean people will be able to enjoy prosperity and freedom and realize their dreams would be built through the Korean Peninsula Trust-building Process. In her inauguration speech, Park presented four guiding principles to realize her administrative vision: economic prosperity, people's happiness, cultural enrichment, and establishment of foundation for peaceful unification.<ref>[http://news1.kr/articles/1024223 News1 Korea: President's Inaugural Address] {{in lang|ko}}</ref> Park's inauguration ceremony was the largest one in South Korean history with 70,000 participants. Diplomatic representatives in Korea as well as high-level delegates specially sent from 24 countries around the world including Thai Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra, U.S. National Security Advisor Thomas Donilon, Taiwanese Legislative Speaker Wang Jin-pyng and former Japanese Prime Minister Yasuo Fukuda also participated in the event to congratulate Park.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20130224000257 |title=Park's swearing-in draws record 70,000 participants |newspaper=The Korea Herald |accessdate=16 October 2015|date=24 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/foreign-affairs/2013/02/26/371364/Legislative-Speaker.htm |title=Legislative Speaker Wang attends S. Korea president's inauguration |newspaper=[[China Post]] |accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== First year (February 2013&nbsp;\u2013 February 2014) ===\n==== Administrative philosophy ====\nThe goal of the newly launched Park Geun-hye Administration for governing state affairs was to open \"a new era of hope and happiness for all the people\". Park avowed that South Korea would break away from its long-pursued development model that centered around the nation, and shift the focus of government administration from the state to individual citizens. Through this process the structure of co-prosperity would be created, in which citizens became happy and national development occurred as a result. Park's administrative vision and basic principles for governing the nation were concretely outlined in her policy plans for the economy, society, welfare, diplomacy, and unification. The administration's keywords in managing state affairs were \"people\", \"happiness\", \"trust\", \"co-prosperity\" and \"principle\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.president.go.kr/government/philosophy/philosophy.php |title=THE REPUBLIC OF KOREA CHEONG WA DAE |accessdate=16 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208001650/http://english.president.go.kr/government/philosophy/philosophy.php |archivedate= 8 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==== Government restructuring ====\nRight after taking office, Park restructured the Blue House and government organization to carry out her administrative vision. The Office of National Security at the Blue House, Ministry of Science, ICT and Future Planning, and Ministry of Oceans and Fisheries were newly launched, and the seat of Deputy Prime Minister for Economic Affairs was revived. The Chief of the National Security Office would act as a \"control tower\" for diplomatic, security, and national defense issues, and the Deputy Prime Minister for Economic Affairs for economic, social, and welfare issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.dongascience.com/PHP/NewsView.php?kisaid=20130116100000000656&classcode=0101|title=THE SCIENCE : [\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c\uc815\ubd80 \uc870\uc9c1\uac1c\ud3b8\uc548]\ubbf8\ub798\u90e8, \uc131\uc7a5\ub3d9\ub825 \ucc3d\ucd9c\u2026 \ubd80\ucd1d\ub9ac\ub294 \uc815\ucc45 \ucd1d\uad04|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Foreign policy ====\n===== United States =====\n[[File:Park Geun-Hye meeting with Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|Park Geun-hye at a bilateral meeting with [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] on 7 May 2013]]\nAfter taking office, Park met with John Kerry and U.S. President Barack Obama. Park's trip to the United States in May 2013 was her first foreign trip after taking office.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Scott |last2=DeYoung |first2=Karen |date=7 May 2013 |title=Obama, South Korea's Park present united front against North Korea at joint appearance |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/obama-south-koreas-park-present-united-front-against-north-korea-at-joint-appearance/2013/05/07/e06767f8-b743-11e2-92f3-f291801936b8_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLike many of her predecessors, Park has maintained a close relationship with the U.S., which has over [[United States Forces Korea|20,000 soldiers stationed in South Korea]]. During her visit to the U.S., she addressed a joint session of the U.S. Congress, where she called for a united front against any North Korean provocations. Park also called for a strong global relationship between South Korea and the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sbs.co.kr/section_news/news_read.jsp?news_id=N1001774050|title=SBS \ub274\uc2a4 :: \ub9ac\ub2e4\uc774\ub809\ud2b8 \ud398\uc774\uc9c0|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=7 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nPark assesses the security situation on the Korean Peninsula and emphasized that deterrence capabilities were the most important factor for security. Thus, Park considers the American-South Korean alliance as the most successful one in the world. And she hopes the American-South Korean relationship can be upgraded from a comprehensive strategic alliance to a global partnership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.korea.net/NewsFocus/Policies/view?articleID=113093|title=Korea.net : The official website of the Republic of Korea|author=Korean Culture and Information Service (KOCIS)|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nPark visited the United States on her first overseas trip as president. She traveled to Washington, D.C., New York City, and Los Angeles on 5\u20139 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.president.go.kr/pre_activity/latest/latest_view.php?uno=7800 |title=THE REPUBLIC OF KOREA CHEONG WA DAE |accessdate=16 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203194837/http://english.president.go.kr/pre_activity/latest/latest_view.php?uno=7800 |archivedate= 3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nDuring summit talks in May at the White House, Presidents Park and Obama adopted a joint declaration for the American-South Korean alliance and discussed ways to further develop the bilateral relations in a future-forward manner. Also, two leaders discussed ways to promote cooperation in building peace in the Northeast Asian region and strength the partnership between Seoul and Washington.<ref name=\"korea.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.korea.net/NewsFocus/Policies/view?articleID=107794|title=Korea.net : The official website of the Republic of Korea|author=Korean Culture and Information Service (KOCIS)|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe two leaders of South Korea and the United States agreed to adopt a joint statement on comprehensive energy cooperation to build a foundation for a future growth engine and establish a policy cooperation committee on information and communication technology. In addition, President Park urged her U.S. counterpart to expand the annual U.S. visa quota for South Korean professionals in order to promote co-development of both economies.<ref name=\"korea.net\" />\n\nIn particular, the \"Joint declaration in commemoration of the 60th anniversary of the Alliance between the Republic of Korea and the United States of America\" adopted by South Korea and the United States will become a meaningful document looking back at the past six decades of the alliance and spelling out a new direction for the development of bilateral relations over the coming decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.president.go.kr/pre_activity/speeches/speeches_view.php?board_no=E03&uno=7820 |title=THE REPUBLIC OF KOREA CHEONG WA DAE |accessdate=16 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204055451/http://english.president.go.kr/pre_activity/speeches/speeches_view.php?board_no=E03&uno=7820 |archivedate= 4 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===== North Korea =====\nNorth Korea had engaged in provocations such as violating a UN Security Council resolution and firing a long-range missile on 12 December 2012, just before 19 December presidential election. After Park was elected, North Korea conducted its third nuclear test 12 February 2013, nullified the non-aggression agreements between the two countries on 8 March and withdrew North Korean workers from the Kaesong Industrial Complex on 8 April.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-15278612 | work=BBC News | title=North Korea profile | date=26 March 2014}}</ref> Park maintained her stance that South Korea will not succumb to the North's provocations and threats, and will endeavor to elicit policy coordination towards North Korea with major powers such as the United States, China and the UN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/2013/04/the-us-should-support-new-south-korean-presidents-approach-to-north-korea|title=South Korean President Park Geun-hye's North Korean Strategy|work=The Heritage Foundation|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> Her response to North Korean issues gained the support of many South Koreans and also the United States, China, and Russia, and played a significant role in the unanimous adoption by the UN Security Council of Resolution 2094 regarding North Korea on 7 March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://csis.org/publication/un-security-council-passes-new-resolution-2094-north-korea|title=UN Security Council Passes New Resolution 2094 on North Korea|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> Due to Park's response and the international community's actions, on 6 June North Korea ceased provocations and threats towards the South and suggested holding discussions on reopening the Kaesong Industrial Complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2013/06/06/0200000000AKR20130606082000014.HTML|title=\u5317, \ub0a8\ubd81 \ub2f9\uad6d\uac04 \ud68c\ub2f4 \uc804\uaca9 \uc81c\uc758\u2026\uc815\ubd80 '\uc218\uc6a9'|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=5 June 2013}}</ref>\nPark said that peace and unification on the Korean peninsula is the wish of all 70 million Koreans and that as president she will do her utmost to meet such a goal. As well, \"the ultimate objective of reunification efforts is to improve the quality of life of people in both Koreas, to further expand freedom and human rights, and [from there] build a prosperous Korean Peninsula.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-34876444|title=North and South Korea to hold talks next week|publisher=BBC|accessdate=16 December 2015|work=BBC News|date=20 November 2015}}</ref> She later stated, \"to open a new era of peace and hope on the peninsula, North Korea needs to accept her administration's trust building policy initiative\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2013/06/06/25/0301000000AEN20130606002500315F.HTML|title=(LEAD) S. Korean president calls on Pyongyang to accept 'trust building' process|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=6 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/south-korean-president-park-geun-hye-answers-questions/2013/05/07/d7482e5a-b761-11e2-b94c-b684dda07add_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]] | title=South Korean President Park Geun-hye answers questions|date=7 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nPark's policy vision and initiative on issues concerning North Korea and unification are reflected in her Korean Peninsula Trust-building Process. The Ministry of Unification has announced a new vision statement \"realizing a new unified Korea that ensures everyone's happiness\". The administrative tasks for this cause include normalizing inter-Korean relations through a trust-building process, embarking on small-scale unification projects that will lead to a complete integration of the two Koreas, and taking practical measures to prepare for unification by strengthening unification capabilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eng.unikorea.go.kr/CmsWeb/viewPage.req?idx=PG0000000694|title=unikorea|last=asadal|publisher=eng.unikorea.go.kr}}</ref> According to Park, peaceful unification will be achieved in a three-stage unification initiative: starting from securing peace, going through economic integration, and finally reaching political integration. To achieve sustainable peace by the initiative, the new administration will offer humanitarian assistance for the people in North Korea, inter-Korean exchange and cooperation in economic, social and cultural areas, and will apply 'Vision Korea project' for establishing a single economic community in the Korean Peninsula, conditioned on sufficient mutual trust and progress in denuclearizing North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://csis.org/publication/trust-underlying-philosophy-park-geun-hye-administration|title=Trust \u2013 The Underlying Philosophy of the Park Geun-Hye Administration|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===== China =====\n[[File:Korea China Press Conference 20130627 03.jpg|thumb|Park Geun-hye and Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]], Beijing, 27 June 2013]]\nOn 27\u201330 June 2013, Park visited China with a South Korean delegation, where she met with [[Xi Jinping]], the Chinese president. During the meetings, Park explained the government's stance on North Korea and gained his support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sbs.co.kr/section_news/news_read.jsp?news_id=N1001856266|title=SBS \ub274\uc2a4 :: \ub9ac\ub2e4\uc774\ub809\ud2b8 \ud398\uc774\uc9c0|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===== Russia =====\nOn 13 November 2013, Park held an extended summit with President Vladimir Putin, whose visit to South Korea was the first among leaders of 4 major powers including the United States, China, and Japan. During the summit, Park and Putin had a comprehensive and productive dialogue with focus on improving economic relations such as logistics cooperation projects (through Russia and North Korea), expanding people-to-people exchanges, and strengthening political ties between South Korea and Russia. Park, especially, emphasized on making preparations to produce an outcome that corresponds to common interests by combining Korea's Eurasian Initiative and Russia's Asia-Pacific Policy. After the summit, both presidents issued a joint communique and held a joint press conference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2013/11/12/10/0301000000AEN20131112007053315F.html|title=(3rd LD) S. Korea to participate in Russian-led rail, port development project in N. Korea|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.president.go.kr/news/newsList.php?srh%5Byear%5D=2013&srh%5Bmonth%5D=11&srh%5Bpage%5D=3&srh%5Bview_mode%5D=detail&srh%5Bseq%5D=325&srh%5Bdetail_no%5D=37 |title=\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \uccad\uc640\ub300 |publisher=president.go.kr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192925/http://www1.president.go.kr/news/newsList.php?srh%5Byear%5D=2013&srh%5Bmonth%5D=11&srh%5Bpage%5D=3&srh%5Bview_mode%5D=detail&srh%5Bseq%5D=325&srh%5Bdetail_no%5D=37 |archivedate=2 January 2014 }}</ref> Earlier, Park attended the G-20 Summit at St. Petersburg in September 2013, where she met Putin for a separate dialogue discussing economic cooperation and seeking support on North Korean issues. It marked the first Korea-Russia summit talk since Park's inauguration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2013/09/07/13/0200000000AEN20130907000100315F.html|title=Park seeks Russia's support in resolving North Korean nuclear standoff|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> When Park met with Russian Minister for the Development of Russian Far East Viktor Ishaev, who headed the Russian delegation to Park's inaugural ceremony, she stated that Russia is one of Korea's key strategic partners, and the successful launch of the Naro rocket is the outcome of mutually beneficial relations and demonstrates that relations will grow stronger in the future. She also noted that Russia's active participation in the six-party talks will contribute to alleviating tension on the Korean Peninsula.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rg.ru/2013/02/26/reg-dfo/ishaev-anons.html|title=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0418\u0448\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0439\u0446\u0435\u0432 \u043a \u0441\u043e\u0432\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0430|work=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic policy ====\n[[File:KOCIS Korea President Park Sejong Econ 03 (11640577615).jpg|thumb|250px|President Park Geun-hye delivering the keynote speech during an economic policy meeting on December 27 at the Sejong Government Complex.]]\nPark announced her plan to build a \"Creative Economy\" on 5 June 2013, representing her vision for economic revival and job creation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msip.go.kr/UserBbs_bbsDetail.action?bbsId%3D72%26bbsNo%3D810%26bbsType%3Ddefault%26manuId%3D128%26insteadMenuId%3D0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=21 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819054534/http://www.msip.go.kr/UserBbs_bbsDetail.action?bbsId=72 |archivedate=19 August 2013 }}</ref> In April, Park said \"Timing is very important for our economic policy, jobs and livelihood mainly ordinary people should organize a supplementary budget in a timely manner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=034&aid=0002478911|title = \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ub300\ud1b5\ub839, \"\uc77c\uc790\ub9ac\u00b7\uc11c\ubbfc \uc704\uc8fc\ub85c \uc870\uc18d\ud788 \ucd94\uacbd \ud3b8\uc131\"|date = 3 April 2013|accessdate = 3 April 2013}}</ref> On 8 April 2014, Park signed the [[Australia\u2013Korea Free Trade Agreement]] with Australia's Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-08/australia-signs-south-korea-trade-deal/5375600 Australia signs free trade agreement with South Korea in Seoul]; ABC; 8 April 2014</ref>\n\n==== Social policy ====\nPark proposed the eradication of \"Four Major Social Evils\" (\uc0ac \ub300\ud68c\uc545:\n\"sa dae hwe ak\")&nbsp;\u2013 sexual violence, domestic violence, school violence and unsafe food. Statistics show that sexual violence and domestic violence are increasing in these years. Without referring to statistical data, aggravating school violence or food safety is a public concern in South Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2972066|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130609085225/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2972066|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 June 2013|title=The zeitgeist: Rooting out social vices|date=24 May 2013|newspaper=JoongAng Ilbo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:4\ub300 \uc0ac\ud68c\uc545 \uadfc\uc808 \uc704\ud55c \ucd94\uc9c4\ubcf8\ubd80 \ubc1c\uc871\uc2dc\ud0ac \uac83|trans-title=Four Major Social Evils promotion headquarter will be established|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/politics/bluehouse/578152.html|date=14 March 2013|newspaper=The Hankyoreh|language=Korean}}</ref> She also launched the National Unity Committee on 17 June with the purpose to advise the president in the process of resolving various conflicts in South Korean society and establishing a culture of co-existence and co-prosperity. Former Democratic United Party Advisor Han Kwang -ok was named as the head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.donga.com/BestClick/3/all/20130617/55918735/1|title=\uad6d\ubbfc\ub300\ud1b5\ud569\uc704 \uc624\ub298 \ucd9c\ubc94\u2026\ucd08\ub300 \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5\uc5d0 \ud55c\uad11\uc625|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== National ====\nOn 18 May 2013, Park attended the 33rd anniversary of the [[Gwangju massacre]], and expressed sorrow for the victims' family members.<ref name=jooogang20130520>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2971803 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130615204436/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2971803 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 June 2013 |title=Park attends memorial of Gwangju massacre |author=Kang Jin-kyu |publisher=[[Joongang Daily]] |date=20 May 2013 |accessdate=20 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n=== Second year (February 2014&nbsp;\u2013 February 2015) ===\n[[File:Korea US President Obama Visiting 18 (14045206364).jpg|thumb|190px|Park Geun-hye and U.S. President [[Barack Obama]], 25 April 2014]]\n\n==== Foreign policy ====\n===== North Korea =====\nPark proposed three steps to North Korea to help move toward the reunification of the Korean Peninsula, on 28 March in Dresden during her state visit to Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-25/park-looks-to-once-divided-germany-to-spur-korean-reunification.html|title=Park Says Once-Divided Germany Is Model for Korea Reunification|date=26 March 2014|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> She stated that \"Starting with jointly managing rivers and forests running through the two Koreas, we need to expand joint projects that benefit both sides. In that respect, I hope North Korea will attend the UN Convention on Biological Diversity conference to be held in South Korean city of Pyeongchang in October.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arirang.co.kr/News/News_View.asp?nSeq=166779|title=News View \u2013 The World On Arirang|author=arirang, Arirang International Broadcasting Foundation|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\nIn May 2014, Park warned that a new nuclear test by North Korea could lead to \"a nuclear domino effect\", that might provide its neighbors with a pretext to arm themselves with nuclear weapons.<ref>[http://www.nti.org/gsn/article/south-korean-president-warns-regional-domino-effect-if-north-detonates-nuke-device S. Korean Leader Warns of 'Nuclear Domino' if North Conducts Test (May 30, 2014), ''NTI'']</ref>\n\n==== Government restructuring ====\nOn 18 May 2014, Park announced South Korea's \"plans to break up its coastguard\" after failing to respond well during the [[sinking of MV Sewol|MV ''Sewol'' ferry disaster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-27465378#TWEET1132272 |title=South Korea to break up coastguard after ferry disaster |publisher=BBC |date=19 May 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> According to Park, \"investigation and information roles would be transferred to the South Korea National Police while the rescue and salvage operation and ocean security roles would be transferred to the Department for National Safety, not to be confused with the Korean [[Ministry of Security and Public Administration]], which will be newly established\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/18/world/asia/south-korea-coast-guard/|title=South Korean president dismantles coast guard after ferry disaster|first1=K.J.|last1=Kwon|first2=Paula|last2=Hancocks|first3=Jethro|last3=Mullen|date=19 May 2014|work=CNN|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\nOn 19 November 2014, the [[Korea Coast Guard]] and [[National Emergency Management Agency]] ceased control as the [[Ministry of Public Safety and Security]] was founded at the same day.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 November 2014 |title=South Korea launches new safety agency |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-south-korea-launches-new-safety-agency-2014nov18-story.html |work=[[San Diego Union-Tribune]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Third year (February 2015 \u2013 February 2016) ===\n==== Foreign policy ====\n[[File:Prime Minister Narendra Modi meeting South Korean President Park Geun-hye on the sidelines of the14th ASEAN-India Summit.jpg|thumb|South Korean President Park Geun-hye meeting Prime Minister Narendra Modi on the sidelines of the 14th ASEAN-India Summit]]\n\n===== China =====\nOn 26 May 2015, Park urged the head of the [[Asian Development Bank]] to cooperate with South Korea and the China-led [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Park calls for cooperation with China-led AIIB|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2015/05/26/9/0301000000AEN20150526009300315F.html|accessdate=12 June 2015|agency=Yonhap News Agency|date=26 May 2015}}</ref> after South Korea had officially applied to join the Chinese-led [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] in late March 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jun|first1=Kwanwoo|last2=Gale|first2=Alastair|title=South Korea Says It Will Join China-Led Investment Bank|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korea-says-it-will-join-china-led-asia-infrastructure-investment-bank-1427373167|accessdate=12 June 2015|agency=The Wall Street Journal|date=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Fourth and fifth year (February 2016 \u2013 March 2017) ===\n==== Foreign policy ====\n===== Iran =====\n[[File:South Korean President Park Geun-hye arrived in Iran, Mehrabad Airport, Tehran 07.jpg|thumb|Park Geun-hye being welcomed by Iran's business minister, [[Mohammad Reza Nematzadeh]] in [[Mehrabad Airport]]]]\nOn 1 May 2016, Park became the first South Korean president to visit [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2016/05/01/0301000000AEN20160501000200315.html|title=Park leaves for Iran for talks with Rouhani|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016|date=May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mehrnews.com/news/116253/Korean-pres-makes-historic-visit-to-Tehran|title=Korean pres. makes historic visit to Tehran|date=1 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> She was at the head of a 236-member delegation of businessmen and entrepreneurs during a three-day visit to [[Tehran]] to discuss bilateral trade and other matters of mutual interest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehrantimes.com/news/301078/Park-on-landmark-visit-to-Tehran-economy-high-on-agenda|title=Park on landmark visit to Tehran, economy high on agenda|date=1 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> She met Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] and held talks with Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.ir/Detail/2016/04/30/463274/Iran-South-Korea-President-Park-visit-/|title=PressTV-Korean pres., biggest trade team woo Iran|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> The two countries also signed 19 basic agreements to expand mutual cooperation over a variety of areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2016/05/02/463612/Iran-South-Korea-sign-19-agreements/|title=PressTV-Iran, South Korea sign 19 agreements|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> Earlier, Iran's President Rouhani emphasized that Iran and South Korea are set to boost their trade volume from the current $6 billion to $18 billion.\n\n==== 2016 general elections ====\nPark suffered a serious setback in the [[2016 South Korean legislative election|2016 general elections]] on 13 April 2016, as the Saenuri Party lost both its majority and its status as first party in the National Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/1935845/south-korean-election-setback-deals-severe-blow-president-park|title=South Korean election setback deals severe blow to President Park Geun-hye's economic reform agenda|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> Park had been criticized for her involvement in the elections and the party's nomination process,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/03/116_200839.html|title=Park's election meddling may backfire|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=21 March 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/03/116_201181.html|title=Park may stay in power after 2018|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=25 March 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> and other Saenuri members blamed the pro-Park faction in the party for the defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202637.html|title= Saenuri's defeat brewing political upheaval|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> Park loyalists fared badly in constituency elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202549.html|title=Park loyalists tumble|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> The result was seen to hinder the chances of Park's passing her proposed economic reforms,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/conservative-rout-leaves-south-koreas-park-geunhye-a-lame-duck/news-story/16ca1208ddd42854cf92dae327574176?nk=c07dd96332972d39c73e50067a02b460-1460645891|title=Conservative rout leaves South Korea's Park Geun-hye a lame duck|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> and in the aftermath of the results the conservative ''[[The Chosun Ilbo]]'' stated that Park's \"lame duck period has started earlier than any other administration in the past\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southkorea-election-idUSKCN0XA2LC|title=Vote defeat for South Korea's Park raises 'lame duck' prospect|work=[[Reuters]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Approval ratings ===\n[[File:Park Geun-hye Presidential Approval Rating.svg|thumbnail|right|Park Geun-hye's Presidential Job Approval Rating]]\n[[File:Park Geun-hye Approval ratings by age.svg|thumb|right|Approval ratings by age]]\nIn July 2013, public support for Park's method of governing state affairs reached up to 63 per cent, much higher than the percentage of the votes she had won in the presidential election, which was 52 per cent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=449|title=\ud55c\uad6d\uac24\ub7fd\uc870\uc0ac\uc5f0\uad6c\uc18c|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> The Korean media explained that such a high level of support comes from Park's principled North Korea policy, constructive outcomes from visits to the United States and China, and distancing away from internal political disputes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mt.co.kr/view/mtview.php?type=1&no=2013070515551873288&outlink=1|title=\u6734\ub300\ud1b5\ub839, \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 63% \uae09\ubc18\ub4f1\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\ucde8\uc784\ud6c4 \ucd5c\uace0|author=MoneyToday|publisher=|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy January 2015, Park's approval rating had fallen to 30 per cent, partly due to the [[sinking of MV Sewol|sinking of MV ''Sewol'']] and disputes with North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/01/116_172335.html|title=Park's popularity hits new low|date=23 January 2015|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> By September 2015, Park's approval had increased to 54 percent due to her diplomacy that defused a military standoff with North Korea,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-04/south-korea-president-park-s-approval-highest-in-year-and-a-half |title=South Korea President Park's Approval Highest in Year-and-a-Half|date= 3 September 2015 |accessdate= 29 December 2015|publisher=bloomberg.com}}</ref> but in the aftermath of her party's 2016 election loss, her ratings fell to 31.5 per cent, plunging 8.1 percentage points compared to the week before the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202869.html |title=Park and Saenuri's approval ratings dip to new lows |newspaper=[[The Korea Times]] |date=18 April 2016 |accessdate=19 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504210254/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202869.html |archivedate=4 May 2016  }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2016, Park's ratings fell to 4\u20135% as details of her relationship with [[Choi Soon-sil]] were investigated and exposed in what became the [[2016 South Korean political scandal]].<ref name=Gallup2016111/><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/south-koreas-presidency-on-the-brink-of-collapse-as-scandal-grows/2016/10/28/7639a2cc-1700-4ef7-a3a4-661b3ff989c4_story.html|title=South Korea's presidency 'on the brink of collapse' as scandal grows|date=29 October 2016|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name=\"sports.khan.co.kr\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.khan.co.kr/culture/sk_index.html?art_id=201612021024003&sec_id=560901|title=\ud55c\uad6d\uac24\ub7fd \uc5ec\ub860\uc870\uc0ac, \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 4%|date=2 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest and detention==\nPark was arrested on 31 March 2017, and held in pre-trial detention at the Seoul Detention Center in [[Uiwang]], [[Gyeonggi Province]].<ref>{{cite news |quote=Park, who was awaiting the ruling at a room of the Seoul Central Prosecutors' Office, was taken to the Seoul Detention Center in Uiwang, Gyeonggi Province, soon after the decision was announced. Park \u2013 in prison garb \u2013 is expected to travel back and forth to the prosecutors' office for additional questioning before being formally indicted. |first=Si-soo |last=Park |date=31 March 2017 |access-date=1 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401040413/https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/03/251_226702.html |archive-date=1 April 2017 |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/03/251_226702.html |newspaper=[[The Korea Times]] |title=PARK GEUN-HYE ARRESTED}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2017/03/31/ousted-south-korean-leader-goes-from-presidential-palace-to-solitary-cell.html |first=Tong-Hyung |last=Kim |publisher=[[The Associated Press]] via [[The Toronto Star]] |title=Ousted South Korean leader goes from presidential palace to solitary cell |date=31 March 2017 |access-date=1 April 2017 |quote=Park Geun-hye entered the Seoul Detention Center in a black sedan before dawn Friday after a court approved her arrest on corruption allegations.}}</ref> On 17 April 2017, Park was formally charged with abuse of power, [[bribery]], coercion and leaking government secrets.<ref name=\"KTCharged\" >{{cite news |date=17 April 2017 |access-date=17 April 2017 |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/04/251_227690.html |title=Former President Park, Lotte chairman indicted on corruption charges |newspaper=[[Korea Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417164527/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/04/251_227690.html |archive-date=17 April 2017}}</ref> Park denied the charges during five rounds of interrogation while in prison.<ref name=\"KTCharged\" /><ref>{{cite news |date=17 April 2017 |access-date=17 April 2017 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/korean-leader-park-indicted-now-faces-trial-46838400 |first=Hyung-jin |last=Kim |publisher=Associated Press (via ABC News) |title=Ex-South Korean leader Park indicted, faces trial}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2017/03/south-korea-scandal-animated/index.html|title=All the Queen's men and women|work=The Straits Times|access-date=12 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Trial===\nProsecutors sought a 30-year prison term for Park, along with a fine of {{currency|118500000000|KRW}} ({{US$|110579397|link=yes}}). On 6 April 2018, a three-judge panel of the Central District Court in Seoul sentenced Park to 24 years in prison and a fine of {{currency|18000000000|KRW}} ({{US$|16,798,683|link=yes}}), finding her guilty of 16 out of 18 charges brought before her.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southkorea-politics-park/south-korean-prosecutors-seek-30-years-jail-for-ousted-park-as-supporters-demand-her-release-idUSKCN1GB0FJ |work=[[Reuters]] |title=South Korean prosecutors seek 30 years' jail for ousted Park as supporters demand her release |date=27 February 2018 |first=Hyonhee |last=Shin |first2=Heekyong |last2=Yang |first3=Christine |last3=Kim |editor-first=Nick |editor-last=Macfie}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2018/04/356_246875.html| title=Court orders 24 years in jail for former President Park| first=Kim| last=Se-jeong| newspaper=[[Korea Times]]| date=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Choe Sang-hun |date=6 April 2018 |title=Park Geun-hye, South Korea's Ousted President, Gets 24 Years in Prison |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/06/world/asia/park-geun-hye-south-korea.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/asia/south-korea-park-geun-hye-corruption-intl/index.html?sr=fbCNN040618south-korea-park-geun-hye-corruption-intl0810AMStory|title=Former South Korean President Park Geun-hye sentenced to 24 years in prison|author1=Paula Hancocks |author2=Yoonjung Seo |author3=James Griffiths|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 three former [[National Intelligence Service (South Korea)|NIS]] directors (Lee Byung-kee, Lee Byung-ho, and Nam Jae-joon) who served in the Park administration were found guilty of bribing, related to the [[2016 South Korean political scandal|2016 Park Geun-hye scandals]]. They illegally transferred money from the NIS budget to Park's presidential office. This illegally obtained money was used by Park and her associates for private use and to pay bribes.<ref>https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/06/15/asia-pacific/south-korea-jails-ex-spy-chiefs-bribing-former-president-park-geun-hye/ . Retrieved 22 June 2018</ref> On 24 August 2018, Park's sentence was increased to 25 years in prison.<ref name=25yearssentence/>\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== Parentage controversy ===\nPark had been often criticized for being the \"daughter of a dictator ([[Park Chung-hee]])\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=003&aid=0003762812|script-title=ko:\uc774\ud574\ucc2c \"\u91ce \ucd1d\uc120\uc2b9\ub9ac \uc2dc \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ubcc4\uba85\uc740 '\ub3c5\uc7ac\uc790\uc758 \ub538'\"|trans-title= Lee Hae-chan, \"If the oppositions win the legislative election, Park Geun-hye's nickname will change (from Queen of election) to daughter of a dictator\"|date=24 March 2011|accessdate=16 May 2012|language=Korean|work=NewsIs|author=Chang Jin-bok(\uc7a5\uc9c4\ubcf5)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newshankuk.com/news/content.asp?news_idx=2011011017184489054|script-title=ko:\uc190\ud559\uaddc \"\ub204\uac00 \ubb50\ub798\ub3c4 \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c\ub294 \ubc15\uc815\ud76c\uc758 \ub538\"|trans-title=Sohn Hak-kyu, \"No one can deny Park Geun-hye is the daughter of dictator Park Jeonghui\"|date=10 January 2011|accessdate=16 May 2012|work=News Hankook|author=Ko Dong-seok(\uace0\ub3d9\uc11d)|language=Korean}}</ref> and for not actively supporting the Lee administration by supporters of Lee Myung-bak. A national-level poll conducted in July 2012 by a conservative newspaper reported that 59% of participants responded they did not believe Park was a \"daughter of a dictator\" while 36% agreed with the characterization.<ref>{{in lang|ko}} [http://news.donga.com/3/all/20120716/47788962/1 2012 Donga Ilbo article]</ref> Park Chung-Hee's status as a dictator became a contested topic after the 1997 Asian Financial Crisis.  GNP party elites saw this as their chance to revitalize Park Chung-Hee's image, focusing on South Korea's economic growth during his administration, thus steadily changing his public perception.<ref name=\"Lee 377\u2013391\">{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Young-Im|date=21 July 2016|title=From first daughter to first lady to first woman president: Park Geun-Hye's path to the South Korean presidency|journal=Feminist Media Studies|language=en|volume=17|issue=3|pages=377\u2013391|doi=10.1080/14680777.2016.1213307|issn=1468-0777}}</ref>\n\nDuring a recent interview with the [[Cheongju]] broadcast station ''[[Cheongju Broadcasting|CJB]]'', Park commented regarding her stance that her father's [[May 16 coup]] was a \"revolution to save the country\" by stating, \"I don't think it's the place of politicians to be fighting over whether [the events of 1961] were a 'coup d'etat' or a 'revolution'.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/546402.html|title=Was it a 'coup' or a 'revolution'?|date=9 August 2012|accessdate=9 August 2012|work=[[The Hankyoreh]]}}</ref> In a July 2012 survey, 50% of respondents answered that they disagreed with Park's assessment that her father's 1961 coup was \"unavoidable, the best possible choice, and an advisable decision\", as opposed to 37% that agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/544829.html|title=An leading Park in latest polls|date=30 July 2012|accessdate=9 August 2012|work=[[The Hankyoreh]]}}</ref> From another survey conducted in July 2012, 42% of respondents agreed with her opinion that her father's 1961 coup was \"unavoidable\", while 46% disagreed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=312&pagepos=1&search=&searchKeyword=&selectYear=|title=\ud55c\uad6d\uac24\ub7fd\uc870\uc0ac\uc5f0\uad6c\uc18c|publisher=|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nBecause Park inherited strong regional and generational support from her father, as well as the legacy of his economic success, Park's opponents used her father as criticism against her.<ref name=\"Lee 377\u2013391\"/>\n\n=== Bu-il foundation accusations ===\nPark has faced much scrutiny over an educational foundation, Jeongsoo Scholarship Foundation, formerly known as Buil (in reference to the stock it controls in the newspaper \"[[Busan Ilbo]]\"), which her father, and later she, headed. Its original owners claimed in court they were forced to turn it over to her father.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/556901.html | work=The Hankyoreh | title= Park Geun-hye denies involvement in scandal-ridden foundation | date=22 October 2012 | accessdate=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Party criticism ===\n[[Liberty Korea Party]] assemblyman [[Nam Kyung-pil]] criticized the Park-centered nature of the party, regarding its preparation for the [[2012 South Korean presidential election|2012 presidential election]], and stated, \"If we keep seeing the same situation where Park Geun-hye gives a press conference before a general meeting of lawmakers is held, and what she says then gets decided on as the party's position, then the public is going to think democracy has disappeared from the party.\"<ref name=\"Hankyoreh-2012\">{{cite news |author=Seong Yeon-cheol |date=16 July 2012 |title=Park Geun-hye's flip flopping and double-talking |url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/542691.html |work=[[The Hankyoreh]] |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, some have said Park's behavior in the lead-up to [[2012 South Korean presidential election|2012 presidential election]] was a mixture of trend-following and corner-cutting\u2014a stark contrast with the vehement insistence on principle that she showed when she opposed a revision of the plan for a multifunctional administrative city in [[Sejong City]]. For instance, [[Yim Tae-hee]], another presidential candidate of the party, pointed to Park's voting down of a motion to arrest [[Chung Doo-un]], a lawmaker implicated with bribery related to saving banks. Another candidate, [[Ahn Sang-soo (born May 1946)|Ahn Sang-soo]], accused Park of \"saying one thing yesterday and another today\".<ref name=\"Hankyoreh-2012\"/>\n\n=== Spokesman scandal ===\n{{further|Yoon Chang-jung}}\nPark fired [[Yoon Chang-jung]], a [[Blue House]] spokesman who was alleged by [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|Washington police]] to have committed sexual assault against a young woman hired as an intern at the [[Embassy of South Korea, Washington, D.C.|South Korean Embassy in Washington]] during President Park's first visit to the United States.<ref name=ny20130511>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/11/world/asia/spokesman-for-south-korean-leader-quits.html | newspaper=[[New York Times]] | title= South Korean President Fires Spokesman for 'Unsavory Act' During Visit to U.S. |first=SANG-HUN|last=CHOE| date=10 May 2013 | accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref>\nPark has been criticized for picking the wrong people for senior government posts.<ref name=yna20130510>{{cite news| url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2013/05/10/30/0301000000AEN20130510001000315F.HTML | publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]] | title= (4th LD) Park sacks spokesman Yoon amid sexual assault allegations |first=Chi-dong|last=Lee| date=10 May 2013 | accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Election-meddling scandal ===\n{{Main|2012 NIS public opinion manipulation scandal}}\n{{Update|section|date=November 2016}}\nJust a week before the presidential election date, the opposing party alleged that the public servants from National Intelligence Service (NIS) have organized to promote Park's election campaign by way of posting online articles favorable to Park and slanderous to the opposing candidates.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} This political behavior by public servants is strictly prohibited by Korean Constitution.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://korea.assembly.go.kr/res/low_01_read.jsp?boardid=1000000035 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120710041912/http://korea.assembly.go.kr/res/low_01_read.jsp?boardid=1000000035 |url-status=dead |archive-date=10 July 2012 |title=Constitution of the Republic of Korea }}</ref>\nTo prove their allegation, the opposing Democratic Party, along with the police and Central Election Assistance Commission, swooped in the house where the alleged agent of NIS has resided.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} From there, the 29-year-old female agent, later known as Ha-Young Kim, who was running an illegal online election campaign operation such as spreading slanderous postings about the opposing candidate had locked herself in.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} The police could not force to enter the house and the standoff lasted for three days, provoking a tense political standoff.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} The opposition accused the intelligence service of blocking an investigation.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} Park and her party accused the opposition of harassing the woman.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/19/world/asia/south-korean-intelligence-officers-are-accused-of-political-meddling.html?_r=0 | title= South Korean Intelligence Officers Are Accused of Political Meddling | work=The New York Times | first=Choe | last=Sang-Hun | date=18 April 2013}}</ref> Park even said the standoff of the self-lock-in was a violation of a female right in the presidential candidate debate that took place three days before the election.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nLater that night of the presidential debate, Kim Yong-pan, then the chief of Seoul Metropolitan Police Agency, publicly announced there was no evidence of illegal online postings from the collected laptop of the female agent.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} This announcement, which took place three days before the election, was believed to have significantly affected the outcome of the presidential election according to the opposing party.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\nAfter months of probes into the alleged election meddling, the prosecution concluded in mid-June 2013 that Won Sei-hoon, then NIS chief who headed the intelligence agency for around four years under former President Lee Myung-bak, ordered agents to conduct online smear campaign against opposition presidential candidates.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} The special investigation drew a conclusion that the agents systemically intervened in domestic politics by writing thousands of postings on politics in cyberspace through hundreds of different user IDs.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}  Kim Yong-pan, then chief of the Seoul Metropolitan Police Agency (SMPA), was prosecuted without physical detention on charges of abusing his authority to hamper police investigation into the case.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.philstar.com/world/2013/08/11/1078601/news-analysis-skorea-rattled-spy-agencys-political-interference | title= News Analysis: SKorea rattled by spy agency's political interference}}</ref> CCTV conversation between the computer analysts who were analyzing the laptop at police revealed that the police already knew there were illegal online postings against the opposing party's candidates, but the chief of SMPA publicly announced otherwise, an announcement that indicates intentional meddling into the presidential election.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nThe investigation and the trial at court are on-going, and Park faces a political blow.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} However, the leading Saenuri party along with government leaders has attempted to dodge its political fall-out.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} Their effort has involved tipping a rumor to a major conservative media, Chosun Ilbo, about an extramarital child of the Chae Dong-wook, former Prosecutor General, who has approved the prosecution of Won Se-hoon and Kim Yong-pan, which eventually led to his resignation.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2013/09/116_142783.html | title= Prosecutor general calls it quits}}</ref> Yoon Suk-ryul, the director of the special investigation team, which was leading the probe into the election meddling, was fired and returned to his original position, head of Yeoju branch Supreme Prosecutors Office. The investigation of his team has further revealed that the NIS is suspected of having posted 55,689 messages on Twitter for three months until the presidential election.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?biid=2013102264948 | title= Prosecutors are swayed by internal conflict and external pressure}}</ref>\n\nWhether or not the election meddling of the NIS by way of online posts has actually affected the outcome of the presidential election is controversial.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} However, the false announcement by Kim Yong-pan, then chief of the SMPA, has appeared to do so.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} Had the police announced honestly, 14% of the electorate who voted for Park said they would have voted for Moon Jae-In, the first runner-up of the election.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.polinews.co.kr/news/article.html?no=183788 | title= \uad6d\uc815\uc6d0 \uacbd\ucc30\uc218\uc0ac\ubc1c\ud45c\uac00 \ub300\uc120 \uacb0\uacfc \uc601\ud5a5 52.8%}}</ref>\n\n=== Lack of communication ===\nPark has been criticized for holding press conferences with questions and answers submitted in advance. As of 11 January 2015, she held press conferences four times since she took office in February 2013. Among the four press conferences, three of them were public speeches without questions and answers. Even in the remaining press conference, the questions were submitted in advance and she read prepared answers. Her opponents labeled her as \"No communication\" (\ubd88\ud1b5, ''Bultong'').<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:\ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \uae30\uc790\ud68c\uacac |trans-title=Presidential Press Conference |publisher=Jeonbuk Daily |date=11 February 2015 |url=http://www.jjan.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=536421 |language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=News Analysis: Park Geun-hye's first year: principle vs. non-communication |date=25 February 2014 |publisher=Xinhua |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/indepth/2014-02/25/c_133141149.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019050939/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/indepth/2014-02/25/c_133141149.htm |archivedate=19 October 2015  }}</ref>\n\n=== November 2015 protests ===\nOn 15 November 2015, around 80,000 anti-government protesters clashed with government forces on the streets of Seoul, demanding that Park step down, with many of the protesters chanting \"Park Geun-hye, step down\". The rally was triggered by Park's adopting business-friendly labour policies and a decision to require middle and high schools to use only state-issued history textbooks in classes starting in 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Anti-government protesters rally in South Korea|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/11/anti-government-protesters-clash-police-korea-151114085804263.html|website = www.aljazeera.com|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref> combined with plans to make labour markets more flexible by giving employers more leeway in dismissing workers. Security forces fired tear gas and sprayed water cannons into the crowd when protesters attempted to break through police barricades.<ref>{{Cite web|title = S Korea protesters clash with police in Seoul \u2013 BBC News|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-34820596|website = BBC News|accessdate = 14 November 2015|language = en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Censorship ===\nIn the wake of the April 2014 capsize of the [[Sinking of MV Sewol|Sewol]] ferry, public outcry arose over the government's handling of the situation.  In response, the Park administration established a commission to monitor and prosecute social media critics of Park.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2015/south-korea\n| title = South Korea {{!}} Country report {{!}} Freedom in the World {{!}} 2015\n| website = freedomhouse.org\n| access-date = 28 February 2016\n}}</ref>\n[[Tatsuya Kato (journalist)|Tatsuya Kato]], Japanese journalist who was a [[Seoul]] Bureau chief of [[South Korea]] at ''[[Sankei Shimbun]]'' was indicted on charges of defamation for reporting the relationship of President Park Geun-hye and [[Choi Soon-sil]]'s husband, [[Chung Yoon-hoi]],  by the [[Supreme Prosecutors' Office of the Republic of Korea]] after the [[sinking of MV Sewol|MV ''Sewol'' sank]].<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/korean-prosecutors-indict-japanese-journalist-on-defamation-charge-1412826990|newspaper=wsj.com|title=Korean Prosecutors Indict Japanese Journalist on Defamation Charge \u2013 WSJ|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"koreatimes\">{{cite web|url=http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/phone/news/view.jsp?req_newsidx=209657|publisher=m.koreatimes.co.kr|title=US journal criticizes Park's regression into dictatorship|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy about violating Public Official Election Act ===\nOn 25 June 2015 Park said that \"Betrayal which breaks the trust shouldn't be accepted in politics and this should be punished by election with people's own hands\". This mention was aimed to Yu Seungmin who was a member of Saenuri Party. Her mention was criticized by professor [[Jo Guk]] and politician [[Moon Jae-in]] because it had a purpose of losing Yu Seungmin's election which is protected by Public Official Election Act. But the National Election Commission decided not to treat Park's mention as a violation of Public Official Election Act.<ref>Park's mention can be treated as a violation of public official election act http://finance.daum.net/news/news_content.daum?docid=MD20150628171008128 Ruling party floor leader resigns amid party's internal feud / YTN https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dvxXJr4PeIE</ref>\n\n=== Choi Soon-sil scandal and impeachment ===\n{{Main|2016 South Korean political scandal}}\n{{see also|Impeachment of Park Geun-hye}}\nIn late October 2016, investigations into Park's relationship with [[Choi Soon-sil]], daughter of the late Church of Eternal Life cult leader and President Park's mentor [[Choi Tae-min]] began.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/10/116_216623.html|date=23 October 2016|title=Investigations into 'Choi Soon-sil gate' widening|website=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=All the Queen's men and women|url=http://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2017/03/south-korea-scandal-animated/index.html|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nSeveral news media including [[JTBC]] and [[the Hankyoreh]] reported that Choi, who has no official government position, had access to confidential documents and information for the president, and acted as a close confidant for the president. Choi and President Park's senior staff including both Ahn Jong-bum and Jeong Ho-sung used their influence to extort \u20a977.4 billion (approximately $75 million) from Korean [[chaebol]]s\u2014family-owned large business conglomerates\u2014and set up two culture and sports-related foundations, Mir and K-sports foundations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/768777.html|title=\ubc15 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \ub3c5\ub300\ud55c \ub300\uae30\uc5c5\ub4e4 \ubbf8\ub974\u00b7K \ucd9c\uc5f0\uae08 \uc720\ub3c5 \ub9ce\uc558\ub2e4|date=3 November 2016|publisher=hani.co.kr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/opinion/column/768706.html|title=[\uc548\uc120\ud76c\uc758 \ubc11\uc904 \uae0b\uae30] \uc7ac\ubc8c\ub4e4\uc774 \ud53c\ud574\uc790\ub77c\uace0?|date=3 November 2016|publisher=hani.co.kr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.donga.com/3/00/20161101/81099663/1|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]\"\ubbf8\ub974-K\uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc7ac\ub2e8 \ubaa8\uae08, \uc548\uc885\ubc94 \uc218\uc11d\uc774 \uc9c0\uc2dc\ud588\ub2e4\"|publisher=news.donga.com}}</ref> Choi is also accused of having influenced [[Ewha Womans University]] to change their admission criteria in order for her daughter [[Chung Yoo-ra]] to be given a place there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title='Rasputin-like' friend of South Korean president returns amid protests|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/30/south-korea-rasputin-like-friend-president-park-geun-hye-returns|work=The Guardian|date=30 October 2016}}</ref> Ahn Jong-bum and Jeong Ho-sung, top presidential aides, were arrested for abuse of power and helping Choi; they denied wrongdoing and claimed that they were simply following President Park's orders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.donga.com/rss/feed/3/all/20161102/81140663/1?gid=81140910&srev=1&regdate=20161103 |title=\uac80\ucc30, \uc548\uc885\ubc94 \uc804 \uc815\ucc45\uc870\uc815\uc218\uc11d \uae34\uae09\uccb4\ud3ec\u2026\uc11c\uc6b8\ub0a8\ubd80\uad6c\uce58\uc18c\ub85c \uc774\uc1a1 |publisher=news.donga.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104142326/http://news.donga.com/rss/feed/3/all/20161102/81140663/1?gid=81140910&srev=1&regdate=20161103 |archivedate=4 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 October 2016, Park publicly acknowledged her close ties with Choi. On 28 October, Park dismissed key members of her top office staff while her [[#Approval ratings|approval ratings]] fell to 4%.<ref name=\"sports.khan.co.kr\"/> Her approval rating ranged from 1 to 3% for Korean citizens under 60 years of age, while it remained higher, at 13%, for the over 60 age group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.ohmynews.com/NWS_Web/Mobile/at_pg.aspx?CNTN_CD=A0002257639#cb|title=President Park breaks YS's record, approval rating at 5 percent|date=6 November 2016|website=Oh My News}}</ref> It was the worst ever approval rate in Korean history and is worse than the 6% approval rating of former President [[Kim Young-sam]], who was widely blamed for forcing the Korean economy into the [[1997 Asian financial crisis]].<ref name=Gallup2016111>{{cite web |title=\ub370\uc77c\ub9ac \uc624\ud53c\ub2c8\uc5b8 \uc81c234\ud638(2016\ub144 11\uc6d4 1\uc8fc) |trans-title=Daily Opinion No. 234 (1 November 2016) |publisher=Gallup Korea |url=http://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=787&pagePos=1&selectYear=&search=&searchKeyword=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/10/116_217058.html|title=Park orders secretaries to resign over 'Choi Soon-sil scandal'|date=28 October 2016|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> The controversy led to [[2016 South Korean protests|mass protests and rallies]] in October and November 2016 calling for her resignation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southkorea-politics-idUSKCN12T08V|title=Thousands protest in South Korea, demand president quit over scandal|website=Reuters}}</ref> On 12 November, more than 1 million citizens participated in the protests at Gwanghwamun Square close to presidential residence demanding President Park's resignation or impeachment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.kr/2016/11/13/story_n_12936242.html|title='100\ub9cc\uba85'\uc774 \uc9c0\ud558\ucca0 \ud1b5\uacc4\ub85c \uc99d\uba85\ub410\ub2e4|publisher=huffingtonpost.kr}}</ref> On 19 November, another 1 million people participated in the national protest after Park refused to help in the investigation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20161120n00937|title=\ub4e4\ubd88\ub85c \ubc88\uc9c4 2\uc8fc\uc5f0\uc18d '100\ub9cc \ucd1b\ubd88\ud601\uba85'\u202626\uc77c 300\ub9cc \uc608\uace0|publisher=news.nate.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/771080.html|title=Dreaming of a new world, one million candles again burn nationwide|publisher=english.hani.co.kr}}</ref>\n\nPark then fired a number of her cabinet members and the prime minister. In particular, the sacking of the prime minister [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] resulted in a controversy, due to the claim that his firing was carried out via a text message.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.khan.co.kr/view.html?artid=201611032237025&code=910100|title=Left wings outrage regarding text firing of Hwang Kyo-ahn|website=KyungHyang}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.insight.co.kr/newsRead.php?ArtNo=81335|title=Prime minister Hwang Kyo-ahn 'fired' by president Park via a text message|website=Insight}}</ref> The Supreme Prosecutors' Office of Korea (SPO), in laying charges against Choi and two former presidential aides, have alleged that President Park colluded with the three in certain criminal activities. The president would be questioned by prosecutors, the first time this has occurred with a serving South Korean president.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Agence France-Presse|title=Choi-gate prosecutors accuse South Korean president of collusion|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/20/choi-gate-prosecutors-accuse-south-korean-president-of-collusion|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2016/11/20/2016112000593.html|title=\ucd5c\uc21c\uc2e4, \ub538 \uce5c\uad6c \ubd80\ubaa8 \ubbfc\uc6d0 \ub4e4\uc5b4\uc8fc\uace0 1000\ub9cc\uc6d0 \uc0e4\ub12c\ubc31 \ub4f1 5000\ub9cc\uc6d0 \ucc59\uaca8|publisher=news.chosun.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20161120n10972|title=\u6aa2, \ud5cc\uc815\uc0ac\uc0c1 \uccab \ud604\uc9c1 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \ud53c\uc758\uc790 \uc785\uac74\u2026\"3\uba85\uacfc \uacf5\ubaa8\ubc94\ud589\"(\uc885\ud569)|publisher=news.nate.com}}</ref> Following the scandal, there were a series of massive demonstrations that started in the first week of November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/south-koreas-president-park-beast-public-sentiment/|title=South Korea's President Park and the beast of public sentiment|last=Breen|first=Michael|date=29 November 2016|website=www.atimes.com|publisher=|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> On 29 November 2016, Park offered to resign as President, and invited the National Assembly to arrange a transfer of power. The opposition parties rejected the offer, accusing Park of attempting to avoid the process of impeachment.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McCurry|first1=Justin|title=South Korea's president calls on parliament to arrange her exit|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/29/south-koreas-president-calls-on-parliament-to-arrange-her-exit|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 November 2016|date=29 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe National Assembly instead filed a motion for impeachment, which was put to a vote on 9 December 2016<ref>{{cite news|author1=Agence France-Presse|title=South Korean president Park Geun-Hye to face impeachment vote|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/03/south-korean-president-park-geun-hye-to-face-impeachment-vote|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 December 2016|date=3 December 2016|author1-link=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> and passed with 234 supports.<ref name=\"nyt-impeachments\">{{cite news|last1=Sang-hun|first1=Choe|title=South Korea Parliament Votes to Impeach President Park Geun-hye|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/09/world/asia/south-korea-president-park-geun-hye-impeached.html|accessdate=9 December 2016|work=The New York Times|date=9 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Joo|first1=Youngjae|script-title=ko:[\uc18d\ubcf4]\ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \ud0c4\ud575\uc18c\ucd94\uc548 \uac00\uacb0\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\ucc2c\uc131 234\u00b7\ubc18\ub300 56\u00b7\ubb34\ud6a8 7\u00b7\uae30\uad8c 2|url=http://news.khan.co.kr/kh_news/khan_art_view.html?artid=201612091610001&code=940100|accessdate=9 December 2016|work=Kyunghyang|date=9 December 2016|language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/southkorea-politics-idINKBN13X2JQ|title=South Korean parliament votes overwhelmingly to impeach President Park|first1=Ju-min|last1=Park|first2=Jack|last2=Kim|publisher=}}</ref> Due to the ratification of her [[Impeachment of Park Geun-hye|impeachment proposal]], her presidential powers and duties were suspended, and Prime Minister [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] assumed those powers and duties as Acting President.<ref name=\"Yonhap\" />\nPark was finally ousted from office by the Constitutional Court on 10 March 2017. The decision was unanimous, 8\u20130 in favour of impeachment, as announced shortly thereafter.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korea president Park Geun-hye ousted by court|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39202936|accessdate=10 March 2017|agency=BBC|date=10 March 2017}}</ref> On 26 March 2017, South Korean prosecutors announced they were seeking an arrest warrant against Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/27/asia/south-korea-park-geun-hye/index.html|title=Arrest warrant sought for ousted South Korean president|author=Taehoon Lee|website=CNN|access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref> This warrant was granted by the Seoul Central District Court on 30 March 2017 and Park was arrested later that day.<ref name=\"BBC_arrest1\">{{cite news|title=Ex-South Korean president Park Geun-hye arrested|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-39449681|accessdate=30 March 2017|work=BBC|date=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n=== National Assembly races (1998 to present) ===\n==== 1998 ====\n{{Election box begin no change | title=15th National Assembly of the Republic of Korea elections, 1998 by-election, Dalseong, Daegu<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1998040300289101004&edtNo=5&printCount=1&publishDate=1998-04-03&officeId=00028&pageNo=1&printNo=3157&publishType=00010|script-title=ko:\ud55c\ub098\ub77c \uc7ac\ubcf4\uc120 4\uacf3 \uc11d\uad8c|trans-title=GNP won all four seats of by-election|date=3 April 1998|accessdate=16 May 2012|work=[[The Hankyoreh]]|author1=An Jaeseung(\uc548\uc7ac\uc2b9)|author2=Choe Ikrim(\ucd5c\uc775\ub9bc)|author3=Hong Dae-sun(\ud64d\ub300\uc120)|author4=Sin Seung-geun(\uc2e0\uc2b9\uadfc)|language=Korean|quote=\ub300\uad6c \ub2ec\uc131\uc5d0\uc120 \uc774\ub0a0 \uc790\uc815 \ud604\uc7ac 82%\uac1c\ud45c \uc0c1\ud669\uc5d0\uc11c \ubc15\uadfc\ud61c \ud6c4\ubcf4\uac00 2\ub9cc8937\ud45c(51.5%)\ub97c \uc5bb\uc5b4 1\ub9cc 6355\ud45c(29.1%)\ub97c \uc5bb\uc740 \uc5c4\uc0bc\ud0c1 \uad6d\ubbfc\ud68c\uc758 \ud6c4\ubcf4\ub97c \ud06c\uac8c \uc55e\uc9c0\ub974\uba70 \ub2f9\uc120\ub410\ub2e4. [In Dalseong Daegu, 82% votes were counted by 12 am. And Park Geun-hye got 28,937 (52%) votes, compared to 16,355 (29%) votes for Eom Samtak of Democratic Party. Park has been elected by wide margin.]}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|party = Grand National Party\n|candidate = Park Geun-hye\n|votes = 28,937\n|percentage = 64\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party = National Congress for New Politics\n|candidate = Eom Sam-tak\n|votes = 16,355\n|percentage = 36\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n|votes = 45,292\n|percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing\n|winner = Grand National Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==== 2000 ====\n{{Election box begin no change | title=16th National Assembly of the Republic of Korea elections, 2000, Dalseong, Daegu<ref name=\"nec.go.kr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/sinfo/|archive-url